e|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47064038/obrien-and-webster/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=O'Brien and Webster |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=March 15, 1894 |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |page=6}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\"|{{sortname|Milt|Whitehead}}\n|3B\n|data-sort-value=\"940411.940707\"|\n*On Opening Day roster\n*Played entire season\n|Yes\n|<ref name=Whitehead>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/player.fcgi?id=whiteh001mil|title=Milt Whitehead Minor League Statistics & History|work=Baseball-Reference|publisher=Sports Reference|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\"|{{sort|Work, Billy|Billy Work}}\n|RF\n|data-sort-value=\"940521.940629\"|\n*Joined on May 21\n*Released on June 29\n|No\n|<ref name=Work>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/player.fcgi?id=works-001wil|title=William Work Minor League Statistics & History|work=Baseball-Reference|publisher=Sports Reference|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Commons category-inline}}\n\n{{Nashville baseball teams of the 19th century}}\n\n[[Category:1893 establishments in Tennessee]]\n[[Category:1894 disestablishments in Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Baseball teams established in 1893]]\n[[Category:Defunct Southern League (1885\u201399) teams]]\n[[Category:Professional baseball teams in Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Sports clubs disestablished in 1894]]\n[[Category:Sports in Nashville, Tennessee]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Minor League Baseball\n| name             = Nashville Tigers\n| firstseason      = 1893\n| lastseason       = 1894\n| city             = Nashville, Tennessee\n| logo             = Nashville Tigers 1894 second logo.png\n| past class level = [[Class B (baseball)|Class B]]\n| past league      = [[Southern League (1885\u201399)|Southern League]]\n| ballpark         = [[Athletic Park (Nashville)|Athletic Park]]\n| pennum           = 0\n| pennants         = None\n| colors           = Gray, red (1893)<br/>{{Colorbox|#d5d8cd}} {{Colorbox|#c41c1c}}<br/>Golden brown, seal brown (1894)<br/>{{Colorbox|#e4a23d}} {{Colorbox|#59260b}}<br/>Black, white (1894)<br/>{{Colorbox|#000000}} {{Colorbox|#ffffff}}\n| manager          = {{plainlist|\n*[[Ted Sullivan (baseball)|Ted Sullivan]] (1893)\n*[[Dusty Miller (1890s outfielder)|Dusty Miller]] (1893)\n*[[George Stallings]] (1894)}}\n| president        = \n}}\nThe '''Nashville Tigers''' were a [[minor league baseball]] team that played in the [[Class B (baseball)|Class B]] [[Southern League (1885\u201399)|Southern League]] from 1893 to 1894. They were located in [[Nashville, Tennessee]], and played their home games at [[Athletic Park (Nashville)|Athletic Park]], later known as Sulphur Dell. \n\nUnder the [[manager (baseball)|management]] of [[Ted Sullivan (baseball)|Ted Sullivan]], the Tigers finished the first series of 1893 in last place out of twelve teams. Their play was hampered by a preponderance of injured players, which led to high roster turnover and the frequent substitution of local amateur players to make out a full lineup. Consequently, the once robust attendance at Athletic Park declined as the season progressed, eventually putting the team in such dire financial condition that Sullivan surrendered the franchise to the league. They fared better in the second series and were in eighth place on August 12 when circuit-wide financial problems forced the to league disband.\n\nReminiscent of the previous year, the 1894 Nashvilles found themselves last out of eight teams just one month into the season. In contrast, manager [[George Stallings]] made a series of roster moves that strengthened the team, enabling it to move up to sixth place by the close of the first series on June 27. On that date, the league was reorganized as a four-team circuit since financial problems had forced half of its teams to drop out. The Tigers played the first [[night game]] in Nashville some 40&nbsp;years before the first [[Major League Baseball]] game was played at night. On July 7, nine games into the second series, Nashville, sitting atop the standings, disbanded as Stallings and other managers sensed the impending total collapse of the league, which occurred on July 11.\n\nA total of 69 players competed in at least one game for Nashville across both seasons. Of these, 40 also played for major league teams. Among the players who went on to have notable major league careers were [[Bill Hoffer]], [[Con Lucid]], [[Dusty Miller (1890s outfielder)|Dusty Miller]], [[John O'Brien (second baseman)|John O'Brien]], [[Bill Phillips (pitcher)|Bill Phillips]], and George Stallings.\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Formation ===\n[[File:Kimball-house-1890.JPG|thumb|right|upright=1.2|alt=A black and white photograph of a seven-story brick hotel|A [[Southern League (1885\u201399)|Southern League]] franchise was granted to [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]] on October 31, 1892, at the [[Kimball House (Atlanta)|Kimball House]] in [[Atlanta]].]]\n\n[[Professional baseball]] was first played in [[Nashville, Tennessee]], by the [[Nashville Americans]], who were charter members of the original [[Southern League (1885\u201399)|Southern League]] from 1885 to 1886 and played their home games at Sulphur Spring Park, later renamed Athletic Park and [[Sulphur Dell]].<ref name=BTAmericans>{{cite web|first=Bill|last=Traughber|url=https://www.milb.com/nashville/news/looking-back-the-1885-nashville-americans/c-18235116|title=Looking Back: The 1885 Nashville Americans|website=Nashville Sounds|publisher=Minor League Baseball|date=April 25, 2011|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612143127/https://www.milb.com/nashville/news/looking-back-the-1885-nashville-americans/c-18235116|archive-date=June 12, 2018|accessdate=March 5, 2020}}</ref> This ballpark was to be the home of Nashville's [[minor league baseball|minor league]] teams through 1963.<ref name=ComingHome>{{cite web|first=David|last=Ammenheuser|url=http://www.tennessean.com/story/sports/baseball/2015/04/10/nashville-sounds-sulphur-dell-baseball-stadium/25482503/|title=Coming Home to Sulphur Dell|publisher=The Tennessean|accessdate=April 16, 2015}}</ref> In 1887, the city's Southern League team was called the [[Nashville Blues]].<ref name=BTBlues>{{cite web|first=Bill|last=Traughber|url=https://www.milb.com/nashville/news/looking-back-the-1887-nashville-blues/c-9553068|title=Looking Back: The 1887 Nashville Blues|website=Nashville Sounds|publisher=Minor League Baseball|date=April 26, 2010|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612143313/https://www.milb.com/nashville/news/looking-back-the-1887-nashville-blues/c-9553068|archive-date=June 12, 2018|accessdate=March 5, 2020}}</ref> The club suffered financially from poor attendance throughout the season to the extent that they chose to withdraw from the league and disband on August 6 after losing nearly US$18,000 in a effort to cut their losses.<ref name=Am8-7-87>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46623373/falls-through/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Falls Through |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=August 7, 1887 |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |page=5}}</ref> Nashville did not field another professional team for the next five years.<ref name=BRNashville>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/team.cgi?city=Nashville&state=TN&country=US|title=Nashville, Tennessee Encyclopedia|work=Baseball-Reference|publisher=Sports Reference|accessdate=February 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAs early as August 1892, while that season was still being played, a few groups were interested in securing a Southern League franchise for Nashville for the next season.<ref name=Am8-6-92>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46624281/well-be-in-it/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=We'll Be in It |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=August 6, 1892 |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |page=5}}</ref> At the league's annual meeting on October 31, held at the [[Kimball House (Atlanta)|Kimball House]] in [[Atlanta]], the league elected to expand from eight teams to twelve for the 1893 season.<ref name=At11-1-92>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46626818/president-hart/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=President Hart |work=The Atlanta Constitution |location=Atlanta |date=November 1, 1892 |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |page=8}}</ref> New franchises were issued to [[Augusta, Georgia|Augusta]], [[Charleston, South Carolina|Charleston]], Nashville, and [[Savannah, Georgia|Savannah]], which joined the existing circuit consisting of Atlanta, [[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham]], [[Chattanooga, Tennessee|Chattanooga]], [[Memphis, Tennessee|Memphis]], [[Mobile, Alabama|Mobile]], [[Montgomery, Alabama|Montgomery]], [[Macon, Georgia|Macon]], and [[New Orleans]].<ref name=BR1893SA>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/league.cgi?id=3183e972|title=1893 Southern Association|work=Baseball-Reference|publisher=Sports Reference|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> The Nashville franchise was awarded to [[Ted Sullivan (baseball)|Ted Sullivan]], who previously owned and [[manager (baseball)|managed]] the Chattanooga franchise.<ref name=At11-1-92/> The teams pledged to pay a $250 deposit to guarantee they would play the entire season.<ref name=At11-1-92/> They later agreed to set aside 3% of the gross proceeds of each game for a sinking fund to keep the league on firm financial ground.<ref name=At2-12-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46826097/the-league-meeting/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=The League Meeting |work=The Atlanta Constitution |location=Atlanta |date=February 12, 1893 |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |page=12}}</ref> Player salaries were capped at $1,000 with a penalty of forfeiture of games for exceeding that amount.<ref name=At11-1-92/>\n\nIn the weeks leading up to the season, Southern League teams acquired nicknames from their local fans and sportswriters. The Nashvilles were variously referred to as the \"[[Hibernia|Hibernian]]s\", owing to Sullivan's [[Irish people|Irish]] heritage, and the \"Bluffers\", the nickname of spring training player Josh Conley.<ref name=Ch4-3-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46741119/how-they-are-drubbed/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=How They Are \"Drubbed\" |work=Chattanooga Daily Times |location=Chattanooga |date=April 3, 1893 |accessdate=February 27, 2020 |page=5}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46750839/diamond-dust/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Diamond Dust |work=Chattanooga Daily Times |location=Chattanooga |date=April 3, 1893 |accessdate=February 27, 2020 |page=5}}</ref> Sullivan did not want his team called by either of these names. Instead, he preferred \"Nashville Tigers\".<ref name=Ch4-5-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46740991/we-beat-em/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=We Beat 'Em |work=Chattanooga Daily Times |location=Chattanooga |date=April 5, 1893 |accessdate=February 27, 2020 |page=3}}</ref> Both of the city's daily newspapers, ''[[Nashville American|The Daily American]]'' and ''[[Nashville Banner]]'', followed suit by using the moniker in coverage of Nashville's games.<ref name=Am3-13-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46740910/local-ball-team/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Local Ball Club |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=March 13, 1893 |accessdate=March 15, 2020 |page=3}}</ref><ref name=Bn4-11-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46672505/sullivans-tigers/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Sullivan's Tigers |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=April 11, 1893 |accessdate=March 15, 2020 |page=8}}</ref>\n\n=== The first season ===\n==== Spring training 1893 ====\n[[File:Ted Sullivan 1893 Nashville American illustration.png|thumb|left|upright=0.9|alt=A black and white portrait illustration of a man with a mustache wearing a suit and bowler hat|[[Ted Sullivan (baseball)|Ted Sullivan]], [[manager (baseball)|manager]] of the 1893 Nashville Tigers]]\n\nTed Sullivan, who was to manage the Nashville club, secured the lease for Athletic Park and began to sign players.<ref name=Bn2-6-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46640125/manager-ted-sullivan/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Manager Ted Sullivan |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=February 6, 1893 |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |page=3}}</ref> He sought out men he considered to be dependable and who were known as experienced, skilled ballplayers.<ref name=Am2-14-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46628560/base-ball-in-93/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Base Ball in '93 |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=February 14, 1893 |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |page=3}}</ref> Nine of the thirteen who began the season with Nashville had prior experience on [[Major League Baseball|major league]] teams.<ref name=BR1893>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/team.cgi?id=7aa3432e|title=1893 Nashville Tigers Statistics|work=Baseball-Reference|publisher=Sports Reference|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> Some of the more seasoned major leaguers Sullivan acquired were [[Sam LaRocque]],<ref name=LaRocque>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/player.fcgi?id=larocq001sam|title=Sam LaRocque Minor League Statistics & History|work=Baseball-Reference|publisher=Sports Reference|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> [[Tom O'Brien (second baseman)|Tom O'Brien]],<ref name=TOBrien>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/player.fcgi?id=obrien001tom|title=Tom O'Brien Minor League Statistics & History|work=Baseball-Reference|publisher=Sports Reference|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref> and [[Tom Vickery]].<ref name=Vickery>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/player.fcgi?id=vicker001tom|title=Tom Vickery Minor League Statistics & History|work=Baseball-Reference|publisher=Sports Reference|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref> Another was [[Bill Geiss]], who also played for the 1885 Nashville Americans.<ref name=Geiss>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/player.fcgi?id=geiss-001bil|title=Bill Geiss Minor League Statistics & History|work=Baseball-Reference|publisher=Sports Reference|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref> Sullivan himself had played a few major league games and had managed big league clubs including the 1884 [[Union Association]] champion [[St. Louis Maroons]].<ref name=TSullivan>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/player.fcgi?id=sulliv001tp-|title=Ted Sullivan Minor League Statistics & History|work=Baseball-Reference|publisher=Sports Reference|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nPlayers were to report to Nashville by March 18 for several weeks of practice and exhibition games before the beginning of the season on April 10.<ref name=Bn2-25-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46640713/booming-baseball/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Booming Baseball |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=February 25, 1893 |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |page=6}}</ref> A few of these exhibitions were played against teams from the [[National League]], the only major league at the time, who traveled south to prepare for their seasons in a warmer climate. Their first two tuneup games were versus the [[St. Louis Browns (NL)|St. Louis Browns]] on March 23 and 24 at Athletic Park. The Browns won the first game, 10\u20133.<ref name=Am3-24-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46650222/nashville-plays-ball/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Nashville Plays Ball |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=March 24, 1893 |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |page=2}}</ref> In the second day's game, St. Louis' players walked off the field in the bottom of the seventh inning following a disagreement with the [[umpire (baseball)|umpire]]. They refused to continue playing, and, though leading 8\u20136 at the time, the umpire awarded the game to Nashville on forfeit.<ref name=Bn3-25-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46650368/ended-in-a-row/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Ended in a Row |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=March 25, 1893 |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |page=620}}</ref> The [[Baltimore Orioles (1882\u20131899)|Baltimore Orioles]] visited Nashville for two games on April 7 and 8. The National Leaguers won the first contest, 3\u20130.<ref name=Bn4-8-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46669588/it-was-a-shut-out/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=It Was a Shut-Out |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=April 8, 1893 |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |page=32}}</ref> The second game resulted in a 9\u20139 tie when it was called on account of darkness after nine innings.<ref name=Am4-9-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46669857/two-good-contests/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Two Good Contests |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=April 9, 1893 |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |page=3}}</ref>\n\nOther exhibition games were played against amateur, collegiate, and minor league teams. The Tigers defeated the [[Vanderbilt Commodores baseball|Vanderbilt Commodores]], 18\u201311, in a March 25 game that was halted after eight innings due to darkness.<ref name=Am3-26-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46650625/vanderbilt-defeated/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Vanderbilt Defeated |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=March 26, 1893 |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |page=7}}</ref> They bested the Vanderbilts again on March 30 and 31, 11\u20130 and 9\u20131.<ref name=Bn3-31-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46651266/nashville-wins-again/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Nashville Wins Again |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=March 31, 1893 |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |page=6}}</ref><ref name=Am4-1-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46667758/a-good-game/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=A Good Game |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=April 1, 1893 |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |page=3}}</ref> Nashville beat a picked team from [[Louisville, Kentucky|Louisville]], 18\u201311, on March 27.<ref name=Am3-28-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46650920/yesterdays-game/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Yesterday's Game |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=March 28, 1893 |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |page=5}}</ref> They split an April 3 [[doubleheader (baseball)|doubleheader]] with the [[Chattanooga Warriors]], losing the first game, 16\u20137, and winning the second, 8\u20136.<ref name=Bn4-4-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46668369/the-broke-even/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=They Broke Even |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=April 4, 1893 |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |page=6}}</ref> The teams then traveled to Chattanooga for two more games on April 4 and 5. Nashville lost both by scores of 5\u20133; the second game was called after the sixth inning on account of rain.<ref name=Bn4-5-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46668695/won-by-chattanooga/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Won By Chattanooga |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=April 5, 1893 |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |page=4}}</ref><ref name=Bn4-6-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/604568482/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Stopped by Rain |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=April 6, 1893 |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |page=7}}</ref> On April 6, on the way home from Chattanooga, the Tigers defeated the [[Sewanee: The University of the South|Sewanee]] collegiate team on their grounds, 7\u20135.<ref name=Bn4-7-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46669261/won-another-game/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Won Another Game |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=April 7, 1893 |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |page=2}}</ref>\n\n==== The first series of 1893 ====\n\n[[File:Joe Burke 1893 Nashville.png|thumb|right|upright=0.8|alt=A black and white illustration of a baseball player with both hands held out waiting to catch a ball|[[Joe Burke (infielder)|Joe Burke]] was one of only two Tigers to play the entire season.]]\n\nThe Southern League played a double, or split, season wherein two [[pennant (sports)|pennants]] were awarded, one to the winner of each series. The winners would then play each other for the league's championship.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46825870/baseball-gossip/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Baseball Gossip |work=The Birmingham News |location=Birmingham |date=January 1, 1893 |accessdate=March 17, 2020 |page=6}}</ref> The Nashville Tigers were set to begin the first series of 1893 at Memphis on April 10.<ref name=Mc4-11-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46689601/vale-o-villagers/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Vale, O Villagers |work=The Memphis Commercial |location=Memphis |date=April 11, 1893 |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |page=3}}</ref> Their [[Opening Day]] roster consisted of [[pitcher]]s Albert Boxendale, Thomas Gillen, [[Bill Phillips (pitcher)|Bill Phillips]], and Tom Vickery; [[catcher]] [[Kid Summers]]; [[first baseman]] Tom O'Brien; [[second baseman]] [[Reddy Mack]]; [[third basemen]] [[Joe Burke (infielder)|Joe Burke]] and Bill Geiss; [[shortstop]] Sam LaRocque; [[left fielder]] DeLoss Wood; [[center fielder]] [[Dusty Miller (1890s outfielder)|Dusty Miller]]; and [[right fielder]] [[Bill Krieg]].<ref name=Mc4-11-93/><ref name=Bn4-12-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46689048/again-defeated/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Again Defeated |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=April 12, 1893 |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |page=3}}</ref>\n\nPrior to the season opener, the Tigers and the [[Memphis Fever Germs]] were paraded behind a brass band through the streets of Memphis to [[Citizens' Park]].<ref name=Am4-11-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46672697/memphis-and-nashville/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Memphis and Nashville |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=April 11, 1893 |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |page=4}}</ref> Nashville took an early lead with four [[run (baseball)|runs]] scored in the first, but came out on the losing end of a back-and-forth battle in the late innings, losing 9\u20137.<ref name=Mc4-11-93/> They were defeated again the next day.<ref name=Bn4-12-93/> After game three was rained out, the teams traveled to Nashville for the Athletic Park home opener on April 13.<ref name=Am4-13-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46691024/our-ball-tossers/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Our Ball-Tossers |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=April 13, 1893 |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |page=5}}</ref> Memphis scored four runs in the first off of Phillips, who was pulled without recording a single [[out (baseball)|out]]. His [[relief pitcher|reliever]], Boxendale, retired the side and did not allow the Memphians to score again. The Tigers came back with a seven-run second inning, giving the home team all the runs they needed to secure their first win of the season, 8\u20134, before a crowd of approximately 1,200&nbsp;people.<ref name=Am4-14-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46693470/memphis-batsmen-puzzled/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Memphis Batsmen Puzzled |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=April 14, 1893 |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |page=5}}</ref> The first in a profusion of season-long roster moves began that day. Geiss, who played the first two games at third base, left the team when Burke was slotted to hold down third in the home opener.<ref name=Am4-14-93/> Phillips, allegedly upset with what Sullivan said upon removing him from the mound, deserted the team after the game.<ref name=Am4-19-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46695716/they-hit-the-ball/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=They Hit the Ball |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=April 19, 1893 |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |page=1}}</ref> Nashville and Memphis met again in a [[doubleheader (baseball)|doubleheader]] on April 15 to make up for the previous day's rainout, each winning one game.<ref name=Am4-16-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46695121/behnes-foul-hit/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Behne's Foul Hit |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=April 16, 1893 |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |page=4}}</ref>\n\nThe Tigers then embarked on a lengthy road trip for the remainder of the month. For the benefit of hometown fans, telegraphed descriptions of road games were to be announced at the Olympic Theatre throughout the season.<ref name=Am4-16-93/> Outscored by opponents 109\u201380,<ref name=Am5-1-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46697959/one-for-teddy/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=One for Teddy |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=May 1, 1893 |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |page=4}}</ref> Nashville won only four out of twelve games on the road.<ref name=Bn5-1-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46697988/at-home-once-more/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=At Home Once More |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=May 1, 1893 |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |page=6}}</ref> They returned home on May 1 in ninth place at 6\u201311 (.353),<ref name=Am5-1-93/> but they were expected to make up ground over the course of the upcoming month-long homestand.<ref name=Bn5-1-93/> In an effort to improve pitching during the trip, Sullivan added [[Bill Hoffer]] to the team on April 21.<ref name=Bn4-22-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46696458/baseball-results/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Baseball Results |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=April 22, 1893 |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |page=7}}</ref> He also released Tom O'Brien at the end of the trip due to his struggles at the plate and acquired Josh Conley to take over at first base on May 2,<ref name=Am5-3-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46724340/victorious-teddy/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Victorious Teddy |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=May 3, 1893 |accessdate=March 15, 2020 |page=4}}</ref> but he was released on May 6 for the same reason.<ref name=Am5-7-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46728067/a-bad-beating/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=A Bad Beating |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=May 7, 1893 |accessdate=March 15, 2020 |page=2}}</ref> [[Billy O'Brien (baseball)|Billy O'Brien]], of the 1886 Americans, was brought in to play the position on May 4.<ref name=Bn5-5-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46726539/another-home-run/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Another Home Run |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=May 5, 1893 |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |page=2}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Nashville Tigers 1893 injured tiger.png|thumb|left|upright=0.8|alt=A black and white illustration of a tiger with a bandage around its head standing on its hind legs and leaning on a baseball bat holding a bag in one paw|A ''[[Nashville Banner]]'' illustration indicative the Tigers' 1893 season]]\n\nOne bright spot of the homestand occurred on May 9 when the recently acquired Hoffer nearly [[no-hitter|no-hit]] the [[Montgomery Colts]]. He allowed only one [[hit (baseball)|hit]], a [[ground rule double]], and [[base on balls|walked]] four batters in the 8\u20130 Tigers win.<ref name=Bn5-10-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46728338/a-clean-whitewash/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=A Clean Whitewash |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=May 10, 1893 |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |page=6}}</ref> Wet grounds at Athletic Park necessitated a premature end to the Nashville games on June 2 and the transfer of the upcoming series with the [[Atlanta Windjammers]] to the away team's grounds.<ref name=At6-3-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46789144/baseball-today/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Baseball Today |work=The Atlanta Constitution |location=Atlanta |date=June 3, 1893 |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |page=5}}</ref> On May 29, the battered Tigers had dropped into last place.<ref name=Bn5-30-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46733537/in-last-place-now/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=In Last Place Now |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=May 30, 1893 |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |page=8}}</ref> Despite Sullivan's assurance that the team would move out of the cellar and into the pennant chase, they ended the homestand on June 2 having won 10&nbsp;games and lost 12, a marginal improvement, standing at 16\u201323 (.410).<ref name=At6-4-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46735731/keeping-it-up/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Keeping It Up |work=The Atlanta Constitution |location=Atlanta |date=June 4, 1893 |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |page=5}}</ref> Sullivan was criticized by the Nashville press for drawing the highest attendance in the Southern League while having one of the worst on-field performances and cheapest payrolls.<ref name=Bn5-30-93/><ref name=Bn5-22-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46731880/saturdays-game/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Saturday's Game |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=May 22, 1893 |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |page=7}}</ref> The ''Nashville Banner'' hypothesized that unless he invested in higher-caliber players, the citizens of Nashville would not long continue their faithful patronage of such an under-performing team.<ref name=Bn5-22-93/>\n\nSeeking to improve matters, Sullivan began making major roster moves in mid May that continued throughout the first half. Changes were so frequent that players were added and subtracted in almost every series. Vickery, frustrated by his own pitching in a May 18 outing, requested and received his release,<ref name=Bn5-19-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46729924/augusta-in-a-walk/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Augusta in a Walk |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=May 19, 1893 |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |page=6}}</ref> but recanted days later and was welcomed back.<ref name=Am5-21-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46731581/pitcher-germans-curves/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Pitcher German's Curves |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=May 21, 1893 |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |page=3}}</ref> Nearly three weeks afterward, still struggling on the mound, Sullivan let him go after a loss on June 3.<ref name=Am6-4-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46735515/it-was-no-surprise/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=It Was No Surprise |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=June 4, 1893 |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |page=6}}</ref> Pitcher Gillen, dealing with a nagging preseason injury, was released after a disappointing outing on May 20.<ref name=Am5-21-93/> Fellow twirler Boxendale jumped the team on June 1, dissatisfied with his standing in the club.<ref name=Am6-2-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46735181/the-recent-rains/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=The Recent Rains |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=June 2, 1893 |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |page=4}}</ref> Center fielder [[Paul Hines]], added on May 24,<ref name=Bn5-25-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46732514/a-very-poor-game/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=A Very Poor Game |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=May 25, 1893 |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |page=6}}</ref> was released four days later due to his poor hitting and fielding along with second baseman Mack,<ref name=Bn5-26-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46732658/feeling-ran-high/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Feeling Ran High |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=May 26, 1893 |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |page=6}}</ref><ref name=Bn5-29-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46733275/three-straights/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Three Straights |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=May 29, 1893 |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |page=2}}</ref> whose indifferent play lost ball games and irked fans.<ref name=Am5-27-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46732968/once-more/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Once More |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=May 27, 1893 |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |page=2}}</ref> Outfielders Krieg and Wood were dismissed on June 2.<ref name=Am6-3-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46735303/ted-couldnt-play-here/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Ted Couldn't Play Here |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=June 3, 1893 |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |page=5}}</ref> Shortstop William Wetterer, who joined on May 27,<ref name=Am5-28-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46733114/the-old-old-story/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=The Old, Old Story |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=May 28, 1893 |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |page=16}}</ref> left the team to be with his dying wife on June 9.<ref name=Am6-10-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46792431/another-one-for-ted/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Another One for Ted |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=June 10, 1893 |accessdate=March 17, 2020 |page=4}}</ref> Outfielder [[Tom Letcher]], added on June 5,<ref name=At6-6-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46791215/rain-once-more/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Rain Once More |work=The Atlanta Constitution |location=Atlanta |date=June 6, 1893 |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |page=2}}</ref> left on June 16 to attend to his ill wife.<ref name=Am6-18-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46793751/why-of-course/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Why, of Course |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=June 18, 1893 |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |page=4}}</ref> O'Brien was lost after suffering an injury requiring hospitalization on June 28.<ref name=Bn7-6-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46798182/the-second-series/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=The Second Series |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=July 6, 1893 |accessdate=March 17, 2020 |page=3}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Billy O'Brien 1893 Nashville.png|thumb|right|upright=0.8|alt=A black and white illustration of a baseball player resting a bat on his shoulder|[[Billy O'Brien (baseball)|Billy O'Brien]] was one of numerous players lost to injury during the season.]]\n\nTo compensate for these losses, Sullivan added catcher Daniel Boland (June 5),<ref name=At6-6-93/> pitcher [[Jack Keenan (baseball)|Jack Keenan]] (June 7),<ref name=Bn6-8-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46792041/one-more-defeat/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=One More Defeat |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=June 8, 1893 |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |page=3}}</ref> shortstop [[Mart McQuaid]] (June 10),<ref name=Am6-11-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46792504/they-played-two-games/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=They Played Two Games |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=June 11, 1893 |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |page=2}}</ref> shortstop Leiter (June 14),<ref name=Bn6-15-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46793134/down-in-georgia/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Down in Georgia |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=June 15, 1893 |accessdate=March 17, 2020 |page=7}}</ref> pitcher Bully Turner (June 16),<ref name=Am6-17-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46793403/atlantas-pudding/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Atlanta's \"Pudding\" |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=June 17, 1893 |accessdate=March 17, 2020 |page=5}}</ref> outfielder Billy York (June 20),<ref name=Am6-21-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46794420/a-cinch-on-bottom-place/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=A Cinch on Bottom Place |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=June 21, 1893 |accessdate=March 17, 2020 |page=5}}</ref> pitcher [[Con Lucid]] (June 26),<ref name=Bn6-27-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46795369/the-national-game/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=The National Game |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=June 27, 1893 |accessdate=March 17, 2020 |page=3}}</ref> first baseman [[Charlie Newman (baseball)|Charlie Newman]] (June 27),<ref name=Bn6-28-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46795547/almost-got-there/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Almost Got There |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=June 28, 1893 |accessdate=March 17, 2020 |page=6}}</ref> outfielders Pat Ready and Laird (June 30),<ref name=Bn7-1-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46796054/drawing-to-a-close/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Drawing to a Close |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=July 1, 1893 |accessdate=March 17, 2020 |page=7}}</ref> and outfielders Hughes and Sowders (July 4).<ref name=Bn7-5-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46798047/augustas-pennant/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Augusta's Pennant |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=July 5, 1893 |accessdate=March 17, 2020 |page=6}}</ref> Sullivan even played himself in right field and pitched a few games beginning on June 20.<ref name=Am6-21-93/>\n\nThough he attempted to strengthen the team with new players, Sullivan had a habit of signing men who were released by other dissatisfied Southern League clubs.<ref name=Bn6-28-93/> Lucid pitched poorly with Macon,<ref name=Bn6-28-93/> Newman was let go by Memphis,<ref name=Bn6-28-93/> and McQuaid was released by Chattanooga for drunkenness.<ref name=Am6-11-93/> He also fielded amateurs he found on the road. Turner was removed from the mound after two batters without retiring a one in his only game.<ref name=Am6-17-93/> Novice outfielders Hughes,<ref name=Bn7-5-93/> Laird,<ref name=Bn7-1-93/> Ready,<ref name=Bn7-1-93/> Sowders,<ref name=Bn7-5-93/> and York also all appeared in one game each before they vanished from the team's lineup.<ref name=Bn6-21-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46794378/macon-has-a-feast/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Macon Has a Feast |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=June 21, 1893 |accessdate=March 17, 2020 |page=7}}</ref> McQuaid was only needed for four games before his release on June 13.<ref name=Bn6-14-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46792907/where-are-they-at/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Where Are They At? |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=June 14, 1893 |accessdate=March 17, 2020 |page=2}}</ref> Leiter lasted just over two weeks at shortstop before his unaccounted for departure on June 29.<ref name=Bn6-30-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46795913/lost-to-savannah/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Lost to Savannah |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=June 30, 1893 |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |page=3}}</ref>\n \nThe first series came to a close on July 4 with Nashville losing both games of its doubleheader at the [[Charleston Seagulls]], 7\u20131 and 9\u20138.<ref name=Bn7-5-93/> Since hitting the road on June 3, the Tigers had managed to win only three games and lose twenty-one. They ended the first series in twelfth place (last) with a record of 20\u201344 (.313), {{frac|25|1|2}}&nbsp;games behind the first half champion [[Augusta Electricians]].<ref name=Reach1894>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/reachofficialame1894phil#page/36/mode/2up|title=The Southern League|work=Reach's Official Base Ball Guide for 1894|publisher=A. J. Reach Co.|location=Philadelphia|date=1894|accessdate=March 19, 2020|pages=36\u201341}}</ref> Sullivan wrote ''The Daily American'' with a letter to fans expressing regret for the Tigers' first half performance and pledging to assemble an aggregation of players for the second series of which the city could be proud.<ref name=Am6-23-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46794786/nashville-didnt-play/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Nashville Didn't Play |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=June 23, 1893 |accessdate=March 17, 2020 |page=2}}</ref> At the start of the season, large crowds came out to Athletic Park in support of their Tigers, but that enthusiasm was on the wain. By June 13, when the team was squarely in last place, accounts of their road games at the Olympic were discontinued.<ref name=Bn6-14-93/> Both the ''American'' and the ''Banner'' supposed far lower turnout was to be expected in the second series if the team continued in the same manner as in the first.<ref name=Am7-3-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46796457/nashville-at-charleston/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Nashville at Charleston |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=July 3, 1893 |accessdate=March 17, 2020 |page=1}}</ref><ref name=Bn7-4-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46796665/the-first-series/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=The First Series |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=July 4, 1893 |accessdate=March 17, 2020 |page=6}}</ref>\n\n==== The second series of 1893 ====\n\n[[File:William Kid Summers 1893 Nashville.png|thumb|left|upright=0.8|alt=A black and white illustration of a baseball player waiting to catch a ball in his glove|[[Kid Summers]] was one of four Opening Day Tigers to reach the second series.]]\n\nThe Tigers were slated to commence the second series with 15&nbsp;games at Athletic Park beginning on July 6.<ref name=Bn7-6-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46798182/the-second-series/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=The Second Series |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=July 6, 1893 |accessdate=March 17, 2020 |page=3}}</ref> Only 10 of the 32&nbsp;players to compete for Nashville in the first half were still with the team at the start of the second, and only four remained from the Opening Day roster. Still on board for the second Opening Day were pitchers Hoffer and Keenan; catcher Summers; first baseman Newman; second baseman LaRocque; third baseman Burke; outfielders Boland, Lucid, and Miller; and manager Sullivan, who occasionally played right field and pitched. Sullivan reiterated his intention to strengthen the team for the second series and began with the addition of outfielder Smith, who played in the July 6 opener,<ref name=Bn7-7-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46852920/lost-the-first-one/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Lost the First One |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=July 7, 1893 |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |page=3}}</ref> as well as shortstop [[Harry Truby]], who arrived July 7.<ref name=Am7-8-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46853278/the-second-one/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=The Second One |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=July 8, 1893 |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |page=4}}</ref>\n\nNashville took an early lead in the second series opener until Memphis tied things up in the fifth inning at 5\u20135. The Fever Germs scored two go-ahead runs in the sixth, but Nashville answered with two of its own in the seventh, making it 7\u20137. Still tied after nine innings, the Tigers went up 8\u20137 in the top of the tenth, but allowed two Memphis runs to score in the bottom half, losing 9\u20138, before a scant audience of about 500&nbsp;people.<ref name=Bn7-7-93/> Adding to the team's troubles, LaRocque was a no-show and Keenan and Lucid both sprained their ankles running the bases.<ref name=Am7-7-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46852883/they-lose-the-first/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=They Lose the First |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=July 7, 1893 |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |page=2}}</ref><ref name=Bn7-11-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46853893/played-good-ball/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Played Good Ball |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=July 11, 1893 |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |page=8}}</ref> Lucid remained in the game, but Keenan had to be replaced by Nashville Athletic Club player [[Newt Fisher]].<ref name=Bn7-7-93/> The next day's game was also a loss behind the pitching of [[John Dolan (baseball)|John Dolan]] on loan from the St. Louis Browns;<ref name=Am7-8-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46853278/the-second-one/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=The Second One |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=July 8, 1893 |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |page=4}}</ref> he was returned after the game.<ref name=Am7-10-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46853684/new-orleans-today/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=New Orleans Today |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=July 10, 1893 |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |page=4}}</ref> The Tigers recorded their first win of the new season on July 8, defeating Memphis 8\u20135.<ref name=Am7-9-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46853416/teds-first-win/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Ted's First Win |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=July 9, 1893 |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |page=4}}</ref> Outfielder [[Harry Berte]] joined the team on July 13.<ref name=Bn7-14-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46854617/keenan-weakened/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Keenan Weakened |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=July 14, 1893 |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |page=6}}</ref> LaRocque failed to appear for the July 14 game, alcohol being the cause, and was released.<ref name=Bn7-15-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46854755/miller-in-the-box/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Miller in the Box |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=July 15, 1893 |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |page=3}}</ref>\n\nAs the homestand continued, a new problem began to loom. Sullivan deemed the club a financial failure, blaming the hardships and injuries incurred by his players for poor turnout and, consequently, low profits.<ref name=Bn7-17-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46855171/birmingham-today/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Birmingham Today |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=July 17, 1893 |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |page=2}}</ref> A group of Nashville investors, led by businessman Perry A. Hughes,<ref name=Bn7-24-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46857743/a-gloomy-outlook/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=A Gloomy Outlook |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=July 24, 1893 |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |page=6}}</ref> formed a corporation intent on purchasing the Tigers.<ref name=Bn7-17-93/> Despite offering the team at what was deemed a reasonable figure, the group was hesitant to agree to its purchase. League president J. B. Nicklin decreed that either the parties come to terms for the sale before the Tigers left on their next road trip or the Southern League would assume control of the franchise and operate it through the season's close.<ref name=Bn7-19-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46855780/it-was-very-easy/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=It Was Very Easy |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=July 19, 1893 |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |page=7}}</ref> On July 22, the sale seemed imminent, but it fell through when monthly player salary expenses were found to be higher than the figure originally presented.<ref name=Bn7-24-93/> Sullivan telegraphed Nicklin, who informed the manger to conduct the Tigers to their next stop in Montgomery on July 24; from there, the league would run the franchise.<ref name=Bn7-19-93/>\n\n[[File:Nashville Tigers 1893 proud tiger.png|thumb|right|upright=0.8|alt=A black and white illustration of a proud-looking tiger standing on its hind legs holding a baseball bat under its arm|A ''[[Nashville Banner]]'' illustration reflecting the Tigers' second series success at [[Athletic Park (Nashville)|Athletic Park]]]]\n\nWhile the sale of the club was being negotiated, the team was performing much better and attendance was rising. On July 19, the Tigers attained fourth place, their highest standing all season.<ref name=Bn7-20-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46856295/nearing-the-top/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Nearing the Top |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=July 20, 1893 |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |page=7}}</ref> Owing to returning fan enthusiasm, the Olympic Theatre planned to resume providing descriptions of road games, and the Climax Saloon on Cherry Street (Fourth Avenue North) would begin doing the same.<ref name=Am7-24-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46858423/off-for-montgomery/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Off for Montgomery |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=July 24, 1893 |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |page=2}}</ref> Sullivan, even in the midst of exiting the team, continued to tinker with the roster. Lucid was released on July 17, after making only one appearance since spraining his ankle,<ref name=Bn7-18-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46855496/five-runs-apiece/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Five Runs Apiece |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=July 18, 1893 |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |page=3}}</ref> and Berte left on July 24.<ref name=Bn7-25-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46858351/hit-keenan-hard/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Hit Keenan Hard |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=July 25, 1893 |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |page=6}}</ref> Though Sullivan received offers to sell off top players for his own financial gain, he refused to weaken the team and even added a player,<ref name=Bn7-20-93/> second baseman [[Dick Phelan]] on July 22.<ref name=Bn7-24-93/> It was thought that with the addition of another good pitcher, the team could be a serious contender for the pennant.<ref name=Am7-21-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46856678/one-more-for-ted/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=One More for Ted |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=July 21, 1893 |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |page=2}}</ref> On July 23, after the completion of the first homestand, the Tigers were still in fourth place with a record of 9\u20136 (.600).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46928053/correct-standing-of-clubs/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Correct Standing of Clubs |work=Public Ledger |location=Memphis |date=July 24, 1893 |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |page=5}}</ref>\n\nKeenan was hard hit by Montgomery in the first road game on July 24, a 14\u20135 loss, and released afterward.<ref name=Bn7-26-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46858621/a-second-defeat/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=A Second Defeat |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=July 26, 1893 |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |page=7}}</ref> This left Hoffer, who pitched the next day, as the Tigers' only pitcher.<ref name=Am7-25-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46858562/a-good-drubbing/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=A Good Drubbing |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=July 25, 1893 |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |page=6}}</ref> As he had earlier in the season, Sullivan put himself on the mound in July 26's game. He got along fine until the fifth inning when he allowed six runs and had Miller move into the box from center field as his relief in the 6\u20135 loss.<ref name=Am7-27-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46859025/teddy-the-twirler/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Teddy the Twirler |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=July 27, 1893 |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |page=2}}</ref> Sullivan offered to continue managing the Tigers if the city would put forth $500 for his services.<ref name=Bn7-26-93/> Instead, he left the Tigers at Montgomery on July 26, and Miller was placed in charge of the club as a [[player-manager]].<ref name=Am7-30-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46859653/shut-out-for-nashville/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Shut Out for Nashville |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=July 30, 1893 |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |page=6}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Dusty Miller 1893 Nashville.png|thumb|left|upright=0.9|alt=A black and white illustration of a baseball player, hand raised, waiting to catch a ball|[[Dusty Miller (1890s outfielder)|Dusty Miller]] became the Tigers' [[player-manager]] after [[Ted Sullivan (baseball)|Ted Sullivan]]'s departure.]]\n\nWhile at Montgomery, the Tigers were left waiting for President Nicklin to send the necessary funds to cover their boarding expenses, salaries, and train tickets to the next series in New Orleans.<ref name=Bn7-31-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46859692/shut-out-at-last/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Shut out at Last |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=July 31, 1893 |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |page=6}}</ref> Also during the delay, Summers, the team's catcher since Opening Day, received and accepted an offer to join the St. Louis Browns.<ref name=Bn7-31-93/> The funds finally arrived, albeit late, causing them to miss the next day's game against the [[New Orleans Pelicans (baseball)|New Orleans Pelicans]].<ref name=Bn7-31-93/> When they did reach the city, they had only eight men, not enough for July 29's game.<ref name=Am7-30-93/> So, they used local amateur Frank LaCourage\tin left field for the three-game series and acquired [[King Bailey]], previously of the Pelicans, who pitched the first game of a July 30 doubleheader.<ref name=Bn7-31-93/> Phelan parted ways with the team after July 30's games,<ref name=Bn7-31-93/> and Smith left after August 8.<ref name=Bn8-9-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46861641/miller-at-memphis/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Miller at Memphis |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=August 9, 1893 |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |page=7}}</ref> These loses initiated the acquisitions of shortstop [[Bob Langsford]] (August 4),<ref name=Bn8-5-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46861055/played-good-ball/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Played Good Ball |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=August 5, 1893 |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |page=8}}</ref> outfielder Sullivan (August 10),<ref name=Bn8-11-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46861991/ten-inning-games/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Ten-Inning Games |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=August 11, 1893 |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |page=6}}</ref> and single-game center fielder Hanley (August 10).<ref name=Bn8-11-93/>\n\nNashville was not the only Southern League team facing obstacles that season. The [[Birmingham Grays|Birmingham Grays/Blues]] were forced to disband for financial reasons, but the league assumed control of the team and transferred it to [[Pensacola, Florida|Pensacola]] on July 27.<ref name=Am7-27-93/> In an effort to decrease travel expenses and keep the league going, it was split into two divisions wherein teams would only play against opponents in their own division.<ref name=Bn7-28-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46859278/southern-league/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Southern League |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=July 28, 1893 |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |page=3}}</ref> About two weeks later, the [[Charleston Seagulls]] quit the league, and Atlanta and Augusta were expected to soon do the same.<ref name=Am8-10-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46861886/rain-and-wind/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Rain and Wind |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=August 10, 1893 |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |page=4}}</ref> The league met in Atlanta on August 11 and decided to end the season on August 12.<ref name=Bn8-12-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46862208/the-end-has-come/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=The End Has Come |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=August 12, 1893 |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |page=2}}</ref> The death of the league was blamed on the circuit being too large with its cities too far apart, an awkward schedule with month-long homestands and road trips, poor attendance, high player salaries, and an outbreak of [[yellow fever]] resulting in the quarantining of the Pensacola team.<ref name=Reach1894/><ref name=Ch8-13-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46865806/the-league-that-failed/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=The League That Failed |work=Chattanooga Daily Times |location=Chattanooga |date=August 13, 1893 |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |page=5}}</ref>\n\nThe Tigers closed out the season with a doubleheader at Memphis on August 12. They won the first game, 11\u20138, but lost the second, 7\u20134.<ref name=Am8-13-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46862514/two-games-at-memphis/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Two Games at Memphis |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=August 13, 1893 |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |page=6}}</ref> They compiled a second series record of 13\u201316 (.448), which put them in eighth place, {{frac|8|1|2}} games behind Macon.<ref name=Reach1894/> Their composite full season record was 33\u201360 (.355), the worst of the league's 12&nbsp;teams.<ref name=Reach1894/>\n\nNashville and Memphis played two exhibition games on August 13 and 14, with Memphis winning the first, 10\u20134,<ref name=Bn8-14-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46862570/the-season-is-over/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=The Season is Over |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=August 14, 1893 |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |page=8}}</ref> and Nashville winning the second, 6\u20135.<ref name=Bn8-15-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46862986/won-from-memphis/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Won From Memphis |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=August 15, 1893 |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |page=2}}</ref> The Southern League had failed to pay the Tigers for the last two weeks of the season, and some players had their season earnings tied up in suspended banks.<ref name=Bn8-15-93/> Miller arranged with the Nashville Athletic Club to play two benefit games with the full proceeds going to his players.<ref name=Bn8-15-93/> The Tigers and Athletics shuffled their rosters so as to make for more even contests. About 200&nbsp;people attended each of the games at Athletic Park, which were played and enjoyed in good spirits. Those in the amateur's uniforms won the first day's game, 4\u20131,<ref name=Bn8-16-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46863245/the-amateurs-win/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=The Amateurs Win |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=August 16, 1893 |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |page=2}}</ref> while the professionals won the second day's, 1\u20130.<ref name=Am8-17-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46863533/athletics-shut-out/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Athletics Shut Out |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=August 17, 1893 |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |page=3}}</ref> The Tigers disbanded on August 16 after the final benefit game.<ref name=Bn8-16-93/>\n\n=== Reorganization ===\n\n[[File:George Stallings 1894 Nashville.png|thumb|right|upright=0.9|alt=A black and white portrait illustration of a man with a mustache wearing a suit|[[George Stallings]], [[player-manager]] of the 1894 Nashvilles]]\n\nIn late August 1893, [[George Stallings]], manager of the Augusta club, came to Nashville to explore the prospect of acquiring the forfeited Southern League franchise and returning it to the city for the next season.<ref name=Ch8-29-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46966342/southern-league/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Southern League |work=Chattanooga Daily Times |location=Chattanooga |date=August 29, 1893 |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |page=1}}</ref> He had offered to take over the 1893 team from Sullivan with the stated intention of selling off its best players, but both Sullivan and President Nicklin ignored the offer.<ref name=Am7-22-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46857112/mclosky-gets-one/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=M'Closky Gets One |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=July 22, 1893 |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |page=5}}</ref> Stallings met with local businessmen to discuss forming a stock company to finance the team, though nothing developed.<ref name=Bn9-26-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46967834/baseball-in-the-south/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Baseball in the South |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=September 26, 1893 |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |page=8}}</ref> Instead, he went in financially with Charles Dooley, who had played for him in Augusta and was to be Nashville's first baseman.<ref name=Bn3-7-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47020794/the-national-game/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=The National Game |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=March 7, 1894 |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |page=3}}</ref>\n\nOn November 6, delegates from the cities previously represented in the Southern League met at the Southern Hotel in Chattanooga to reorganize for the 1894 season. They elected to operate as an eight-team circuit with clubs in Atlanta, Augusta, Charleston, Memphis, Mobile, Nashville, New Orleans, and Savannah.<ref name=Ch11-7-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47017943/and-it-snowed/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=And It Snowed |work=Chattanooga Daily Times |location=Chattanooga |date=November 7, 1893 |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |page=5}}</ref> Macon was later substituted for Augusta.<ref name=Bn2-16-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47019837/the-southern-league/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=The Southern League |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=February 16, 1894 |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |page=2}}</ref> The Nashville franchise was granted to Stallings. It was decided that the season would be contested as one season rather than two halves as it had been previously. All teams were required to put up $250 to guarantee they would play the entire season. Plus, 3% of gross gate receipts were to be deposited in a sinking fund. Visiting teams were promised half of the gate receipts with a minimum of $60 per game.<ref name=Bn2-16-94/> A $1,000 player salary limit was to be strictly-enforced.<ref name=Ch11-7-93/>\n\nThough modern baseball historians refer to the 1894 Nashville team as the Tigers,<ref name=BR1894SA>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/league.cgi?id=8286dfbb|title=1894 Southern Association|work=Baseball-Reference|publisher=Sports Reference|accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref> contemporary sportswriters did not. Instead, local newspapers ascribed that moniker to Ted Sullivan's new Atlanta team.<ref name=Bn6-1-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47141831/ted-and-his-tigers/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Ted and His Tigers |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=June 1, 1894 |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |page=3}}</ref> As was common at the time, baseball clubs were often referred to only by the names of their cities. Accordingly, both of Nashville's daily newspapers called the team simply Nashville or the Nashvilles.<ref name=Bn3-19-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47064988/their-first-appearance/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Their First Appearance |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=March 19, 1894 |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |page=7}}</ref><ref name=Am6-4-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47157148/on-the-ball-field/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=On the Ball Field |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=June 4, 1894 |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |page=6}}</ref>\n\n=== The second season ===\n\n==== Spring training 1894 ====\n\nBy early January, Stallings, who would lead the club as a player-manager, had begun acquiring men.<ref name=Bn1-10-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47018804/letter-from-stallings/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Letter From Stallings |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=January 10, 1894 |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |page=6}}</ref> Five of the eleven who made the Opening Day roster had previously played on major league teams.<ref name=BR1894>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/team.cgi?id=d1275343|title=1894 Nashville Tigers Statistics|work=Baseball-Reference|publisher=Sports Reference|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref> There was some question, however, as to where the team would play. In November 1893, the Nashville Athletic Club, which leased Athletic Park from the city, sublet the grounds to E. G. Connette of the United Electric Railway under the impression that he was acting on behalf of Stallings.<ref name=Am11-19-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46968911/the-local-league-team/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=The Local League Team |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=November 11, 1893 |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |page=5}}</ref> In February 1894, Connette offered to lease the park to Stallings for a given percentage of the gate receipts.<ref name=Bn2-17-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47020026/regarded-as-a-bluff/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Regarded as a Bluff |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=February 17, 1894 |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |page=1}}</ref> Stallings balked at the proposal and threatened to take his team to Montgomery.<ref name=Am2-17-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46244649/may-be-turned-down/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=May Be Turned Down |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=February 17, 1894 |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |page=4}}</ref> Connette gave up the option,<ref name=Am2-18-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46244679/gave-up-the-option/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Gave up the Option |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=February 18, 1894 |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |page=6}}</ref> and Stallings secured a lease directly from the Athletic Club.<ref name=Am2-19-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47020197/it-is-all-settled/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Come to Terms |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=February 19, 1894 |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |page=6}}</ref>\n\nWith the ballpark business settled, players were ordered to report to Nashville by March 12 to prepare for the season.<ref name=Bn3-6-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47020674/nashvilles-vs-athletics/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Nashvilles vs. Athletics |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=March 6, 1894 |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |page=6}}</ref> Some were late to arrive, leaving no time for practice before their first game.<ref name=Am3-17-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47064228/base-ball-to-day/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Base Ball To-Day |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=March 17, 1894 |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |page=6}}</ref> Nevertheless, the Tigers shutout the Athletic Club, 10\u20130, on March 17.<ref name=Am3-18-93>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/46245300/easy-for-the-dudes/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Easy for the Dudes |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=March 18, 1894 |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |page=14}}</ref> They also defeated the Vanderbilt Commodores, 25\u20133 and 21\u20132, on March 26 and 31.<ref name=Bn3-26-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47065318/won-by-nashville/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Won by Nashville |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=March 26, 1894 |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |page=7}}</ref><ref name=Bn4-2-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47078390/baseball-news/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Baseball News |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=April 2, 1894 |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |page=6}}</ref> As to exhibitions with other professional teams, Nashville held two series against clubs from the [[Western League (1885\u20131899)|Western League]], a forerunner to the [[American League]]. The first was a three-game series against the [[Sioux City Cornhuskers]] from March 27 to 30. The Cornhuskers won the first and third games, 10\u20138 and 10\u20132,<ref name=Bn3-28-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47070366/won-by-sioux-city/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Won by Sioux City |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=March 28, 1894 |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |page=7}}</ref><ref name=Bn3-31-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47070810/two-out-of-three/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Two out of Three |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=March 31, 1894 |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |page=7}}</ref> while the Tigers won the second, 6\u20134.<ref name=Bn3-29-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47070534/turned-the-tables/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Turned the Tables |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=March 29, 1894 |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |page=7}}</ref> The other series was versus the [[Detroit Creams]] from April 5 to 7. Nashville won the first two games, 15\u201310 and 8\u20136.<ref name=Bn4-6-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47079055/hit-the-ball-hard/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Hit the Ball Hard |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=April 6, 1894 |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |page=6}}</ref><ref name=Bn4-7-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47079200/won-in-the-tenth/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Won in the Tenth |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=April 7, 1894 |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |page=13}}</ref> The third game was a 7\u20137 draw when it was called on account of darkness after nine innings.<ref name=Bn4-8-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47079308/played-to-a-draw/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Played to a Draw |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=April 8, 1894 |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |page=6}}</ref>\n\n==== The first series of 1894 ====\n\n[[File:1894 Nashville Tigers.png|thumb|left|upright=1.4|alt=A black and white illustration of ten men arranged in three rows, standing, kneeling, and sitting on the ground. They are wearing light baseball uniforms with a dark \"N\" on the chests, dark stockings, and dark caps with light horizontal stripes.|The Tigers' 1894 [[Opening Day]] roster]]\n\nThe Nashville Tigers were to open the 1894 season at home against the [[Memphis Giants]] on April 11.<ref name=Bn4-11-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47079819/opening-of-the-league/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Opening of the League |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=April 11, 1894 |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |page=6}}</ref> The Opening Day roster consisted of pitchers [[George Borchers]] and Jacob Lookabaugh; catcher George Stallings (acting as a player-manager); first baseman Charles Dooley; second baseman [[John O'Brien (second baseman)|John O'Brien]]; third baseman [[Milt Whitehead]]; shortstop Jim Collopy; left fielder Jack Meara; center fielders George Cleve and Edward Webster; and right fielder Pete Sweeney.<ref name=Bn4-11-94/><ref name=Bn4-12-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47095965/resulted-in-a-tie/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Resulted in a Tie |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=April 12, 1894 |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |page=6}}</ref><ref name=Bn4-13-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47097278/won-with-the-bat/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Won With the Bat |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=April 13, 1894 |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |page=6}}</ref>\n\nBoth teams were paraded behind a brass band through the streets of Nashville to Athletic Park. Approximately 2,000&nbsp;people braved the day's chilly weather to welcome professional baseball back to the capital city. Mayor [[George Blackmore Guild]] gave a speech and then tossed out the first pitch before the game got underway. President Nicklin was also in attendance. Each team played well, but there was no winner as the game was called due to darkness in the top of the ninth inning with the score tied, 8\u20138.<ref name=Bn4-12-94/> In the next afternoon's game, it looked like the Tigers would be victorious, holding a 10\u20139 lead in the ninth, but two Memphis runs resulted in an 11\u201310 loss for the home team.<ref name=Bn4-13-94/> Nashville recorded its first win of the season on April 13 thanks to a seven-run eighth inning, besting the Giants, 13\u20136.<ref name=Bn4-14-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47097978/the-fatal-eighth/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=The Fatal Eighth |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=April 14, 1894 |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |page=6}}</ref> The Nashvilles then left for a series at New Orleans. Detailed descriptions of games were to be provided via telegraph at Baxter Court and, later, the Olympic Theatre.<ref name=Bn4-17-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47098508/the-national-game/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=The National Game |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=April 17, 1894 |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |page=2}}</ref><ref name=Bn4-27-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47101328/not-doing-so-well/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Not Doing so Well |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=April 27, 1894 |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |page=6}}</ref>\n\n[[File:George Borchers 1894 Nashville.png|thumb|right|upright=0.9|alt=A black and white portrait illustration of a man wearing a suit and bowtie|[[George Borchers]] pitched in more games than any other 1894 Tigers twirler.<ref name=BR1894/>]]\n\nBefore they left, both Collopy and Whitehead had fallen ill with fevers and fatigue, and the rest of the team became sick in due course.<ref name=Bn4-20-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47099106/club-in-a-bad-way/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Club in a Bad Way |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=April 20, 1894 |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |page=1}}</ref> To make matters worse, Collopy, playing through illness, was hit in the head by a pitched ball on April 19 at Mobile leaving him bedridden and under a physician's care.<ref name=Bn4-20-94b>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47099062/twas-awfully-sad/ |via=Newspapers.com |title='Twas Awfully Sad |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=April 20, 1894 |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |page=3}}</ref> Stallings added outfielder [[Abner Powell]] on April 22 to compensate for the slack created by injury and illness.<ref name=Bn4-23-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47100153/three-straights/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Three Straights |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=April 23, 1894 |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |page=6}}</ref> He also acquired the pitcher Peralto, who tossed a gem of a game against the [[Savannah Modocs]] in his April 24 debut, allowing only two hits and no [[earned run]]s in a tough-luck 3\u20131 loss.<ref name=Bn4-25-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47100740/hard-game-to-lose/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Hard Game to Lose |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=April 25, 1894 |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |page=7}}</ref> Collopy returned to the diamond on April 28, and Cleve and Webster were released the same day.<ref name=Bn4-28-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47101853/nashville-in-luck/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Nashville in Luck |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=April 28, 1894 |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |page=7}}</ref>\n\nBy the end of April, sitting in seventh place out of eight teams with a 4\u201310 (.286) record, the Nashville club started to resemble the previous season's Tigers.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47102493/standing-of-the-clubs/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Standing of the Clubs |work=The Atlanta Constitution |location=Atlanta |date=May 1, 1894 |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |page=8}}</ref> The team was playing well on an individual basis, but under performing as a group.<ref name=Bn5-8-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47130444/knocked-out-again/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Knocked out Again |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=May 8, 1894 |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |page=8}}</ref> Pitching was a key weakness, so hurler [[Sam Moran (baseball)|Sam Moran]] was added to the lineup on May 2.<ref name=Bn5-3-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47129222/it-was-a-dead-heat/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=It Was a Dead Heat |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=May 3, 1894 |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |page=6}}</ref> The Nashvilles returned home on May 9, still in seventh place, with Stallings looking for skilled players that could strengthen the team.<ref name=Bn5-9-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47131341/back-home-again/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Back Home Again |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=May 9, 1894 |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |page=5}}</ref> One such player was catcher [[William Kinsler]], added to the battery on May 10.<ref name=Bn5-11-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47132473/two-in-succession/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Two in Succession |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=May 11, 1894 |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |page=6}}</ref> Following a three-game winning streak against the New Orleans Pelicans from May 9 to 11, Nashville looked to be improving.<ref name=Bn5-12-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47132841/took-all-of-them/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Took All of Them |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=May 12, 1894 |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |page=6}}</ref> However, they proceeded to lose the next nine games,<ref name=Am5-25-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47139563/beaten-nine-games/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Beaten Nine Games |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=May 25, 1894 |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |page=6}}</ref> during which time they dropped to last place on May 16.<ref name=Bn5-17-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47134727/bottom-of-the-list/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Bottom of the List |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=May 17, 1894 |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |page=6}}</ref>\n\nPeralto was released on May 14 on the heels of several bad outings as Stallings had no time to develop the twirler; he needed pitchers who were already playing at a professional level.<ref name=Bn5-15-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47133201/mauled-by-mobile/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Mauled by Mobile |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=May 15, 1894 |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |page=3}}</ref> A series of unfortunate incidents occurred during and after that day's game. Borchers was taken off the mound by team captain Powell. In the dressing-room after the game, Powell verbally berated Borchers, who retaliated by punching the captain in the face. Their teammates intervened to prevent further violence. That evening at the Nicholson House hotel, Borchers approached Powell in an attempt to apologize, but Powell misinterpreted his intentions and broke his cane over Borchers' head drawing blood.<ref name=Bn5-15-94/> The next day, both men were fined by Stallings, Borchers was suspended, and Powell requested and received his release from the team.<ref name=Bn5-16-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47133503/a-slugging-match/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=A Slugging Match |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=May 16, 1894 |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |page=6}}</ref> Sweeney was made the new captain.<ref name=Am5-20-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47135786/ball-tossers-rest/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Ball Tossers Rest |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=May 20, 1894 |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |page=6}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Jack Meara 1894 Nashville.png|thumb|left|upright=0.9|alt=A black and white portrait illustration of a man wearing a suit and bowtie|Jack Meara was one of six men to play the entire season.]]\n\nA number of roster changes began on the team's May 19 off-day in a bid to move out of the cellar. Lookabaugh and Kinsler were released.<ref name=Am5-22-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47136975/rain-stops-the-play/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Rain Stops the Play |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=May 22, 1894 |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |page=6}}</ref> Stallings reinforced the roster with the addition of outfielder Billy Work on May 21,<ref name=Bn5-22-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47137001/only-four-innings/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Only Four Innings |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=May 22, 1894 |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |page=6}}</ref> pitcher [[Carney Flynn]] on May 22,<ref name=Bn5-23-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47137536/took-ten-innings/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Took Ten Innings |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=May 23, 1894 |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |page=6}}</ref> shortstop [[Josh Reilly]] and right fielder Jackson on May 23,<ref name=Bn5-24-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47138586/easy-for-savannah/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Easy for Savannah |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=May 24, 1894 |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |page=7}}</ref> pitcher J. R. Meeker on May 24,<ref name=Am5-25-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47139563/beaten-nine-games/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Beaten Nine Games |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=May 25, 1894 |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |page=6}}</ref> catcher [[Pop Swett]] on May 25,<ref name=Bn5-26-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47140206/it-was-postponed/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=It Was Postponed |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=May 26, 1894 |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |page=3}}</ref> and pitcher [[Sam Shaw (baseball)|Sam Shaw]] on May 31.<ref name=Bn6-1-94/> Amateurs Jackson and Meeker only played in one game each.<ref name=Am5-25-94/><ref name=Bn5-24-94/> Stallings, a superstitious manager, also purchased new uniforms in a different color in an attempt to reverse the Tigers' luck.<ref name=Am5-20-94/> The new uniforms were first worn in a May 22 doubleheader in which Stallings, playing at catcher in the first game, had his finger split open by a swung bat. He had to remove himself from the game and was replaced by John Foreith, a local player pulled from the grandstand. Nashville lost the first game but won the second when it was called due to darkness in the third inning.<ref name=Bn5-23-94/> Vanderbilt catcher Frank Fletcher was put into the next two games.<ref name=Am5-25-94/><ref name=Bn5-24-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47138586/easy-for-savannah/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Easy for Savannah |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=May 24, 1894 |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |page=7}}</ref> Collopy, never seeming to have fully recovered from his blow to the head, was released on May 31.<ref name=Am6-1-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47142486/a-couple-for-teddy/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=A Couple for Teddy |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=June 1, 1894 |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |page=6}}</ref> At the end of the month, in seventh place at 13\u201323 (.361),<ref name=Bn6-1-94/> Stallings instituted mandatory morning workouts with fines for any player not in attendance.<ref name=Am6-1-94/>\n\nPitcher [[George Harper (pitcher)|George Harper]] was added from the Detroit Creams on June 1.<ref name=Bn6-2-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47156074/took-ten-innings/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Took Ten Innings |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=June 2, 1894 |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |page=10}}</ref> Reilly was released on June 5,<ref name=Bn6-6-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47157645/were-left-behind/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Were Left Behind |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=June 6, 1894 |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |page=7}}</ref> and Flynn followed on June 9.<ref name=Am6-10-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47158463/hit-kerwan-easily/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Hit Kerwan Easily |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=June 10, 1894 |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |page=6}}</ref> By mid June, the team had moved up to sixth place at 19\u201329 (.396) and was starting to look a winning ball club.<ref name=Bn6-16-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47159235/two-from-savannah/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Two From Savannah |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=June 16, 1894 |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |page=12}}</ref> Local patronage for road game descriptions, which had relocated to the Board of Trade building, was booming.<ref name=Am6-17-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47159459/the-detailed-report/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=The Detailed Report |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=June 17, 1894 |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |page=6}}</ref> The ''Nashville Banner'' supposed that the club had a good chance of winning the pennant or at least landing near the top of the standings at the season's end if they kept up the pace. With the season scheduled to close in late September, the Nashvilles had plenty of time to move up.<ref name=Bn6-19-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47159744/one-for-borchers/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=One for Borchers |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=June 19, 1894 |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |page=6}}</ref>\n\nUnfortunately, just as it had in 1893, the Southern League was soon in danger of collapsing. The [[Macon Hornets]], who had played poorly all season and suffered financially from ever-dwindling attendance, surrendered their franchise to the league on June 19.<ref name=At6-20-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47199027/macon-lays-down/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Macon Lays Down |work=The Atlanta Constitution |location=Atlanta |date=June 20, 1894 |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |page=7}}</ref> A rumor that the [[Atlanta Atlantas]] were next to drop out began circulating on June 23.<ref name=At6-24-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47199027/macon-lays-down/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Macon Lays Down |work=The Atlanta Constitution |location=Atlanta |date=June 24, 1894 |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |page=7}}</ref> President Nicklin called a meeting for June 26 in Montgomery to formulate a plan to keep the league going.<ref name=At6-24-94/> It was confirmed on June 25 that Atlanta would be surrendered to the league and that Charleston would also jump.<ref name=At6-26-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47200103/a-great-deal/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=A Great Deal |work=The Atlanta Constitution |location=Atlanta |date=June 26, 1894 |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |page=5}}</ref> At the league meeting, it was decided to split the season into two series, the first ending on June 27 and the second beginning on June 29.<ref name=Me6-29-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47203500/will-do-it-all-over-again/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Will Do It All Over Again |work=The Memphis Commercial |location=Memphis |date=June 29, 1894 |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |page=8}}</ref> The first-place Memphis Giants were awarded the first series pennant. Whichever team won the second series would play Memphis for the championship. The league was also reduced to four clubs: Atlanta, Nashville, New Orleans, and Memphis. In a complicated move, the Atlanta franchise folded, but the Mobile team was relocated there to continue the season.<ref name=Mo6-27-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47201343/the-league-meeting/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=The League Meeting |work=The Montgomery Advertiser |location=Montgomery |date=June 27, 1894 |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |page=2}}</ref>\n\nNashville's final game of the first series was a close 6\u20133 loss at New Orleans on June 27.<ref name=Bn6-28-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47162026/it-was-a-great-game/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=It Was a Great Game |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=June 28, 1894 |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |page=6}}</ref> Despite losing all three games in the series, the Tigers were improving and ended the first series in sixth place with a 24\u201334 (.414) record, {{frac|16|1|2}}&nbsp;games behind Memphis.<ref name=Bn6-28-94/><ref name=Me6-27-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47201795/standing-of-the-clubs/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Standing of the Clubs |work=The Memphis Commercial |location=Memphis |date=June 27, 1894 |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |page=8}}</ref>\n\n==== The second series of 1894 ====\n\n[[File:Charles Dooley 1894 Nashville.png|thumb|right|upright=0.9|alt=A black and white portrait illustration of a man with a mustache wearing a suit and bow tie|Charles Dooley went in with Stallings to finance the team.]]\n\nThe Nashvilles underwent a few changes in preparation for the start of the second series on June 29. Borchers was released.<ref name=Bn6-29-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47204058/begin-over-again/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Begin Over Again |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=June 29, 1894 |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |page=2}}</ref> [[Ollie Beard]], who had played for the Nashville Americans in 1885 and 1886,<ref name=Beard>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/player.fcgi?id=beard-001oll|title=Ollie Beard Minor League Statistics & History|work=Baseball-Reference|publisher=Sports Reference|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref> was acquired from the defunct Charleston team.<ref name=Bn6-29-94/> The roster consisted of pitchers Harper, Moran, and Shaw; catcher Swett; first baseman Dooley; second baseman O'Brien; third baseman Whitehead; shortstop Beard; left fielder Sweeney; center fielder Stallings; and right fielders Meara and Work.<ref name=Bn6-30-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47205009/a-good-beginning/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=A Good Beginning |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=June 30, 1894 |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |page=3}}</ref><ref name=Bn7-2-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47205877/quit-in-the-ninth/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Quit in the Ninth |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=July 2, 1894 |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |page=6}}</ref><ref name=Bn7-3-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47206474/took-the-last-one/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Took the Last One |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=July 3, 1894 |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |page=6}}</ref>\n\nThe Tigers and Memphis Giants arrived at Athletic Park in carriages led by a brass band. In the top of the first inning, O'Brien hit the first pitch over the outfield fence for a [[home run]]. Three more runs were scored in the home half of the first, but a Memphis run in the bottom half and three in the second inning tied the game at 4\u20134. The Giants scored five runs in the third, but the Tigers answered with six of their own in the fourth. The game was called due to rain in the middle of the sixth, with the Nashvilles winning the first game of the new series, 10\u20139, before 1,500&nbsp;people.<ref name=Bn6-30-94/> Work was released after the game.<ref name=Bn6-29-94/> They very nearly made it two-in-a-row, but a costly four-run ninth inning on June 30, gave the locals an 8\u20137 loss.<ref name=Bn7-2-94/> With a win over Memphis on July 2, the Tigers moved into a tie for first place with Atlanta,<ref name=Bn7-3-94/> and then took sole possession of first with a win over the Atlantas on July 3.<ref name=Bn7-4-94a>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47207095/nashville-on-top/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Nashville on Top |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=July 4, 1894 |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |page=2}}</ref> Nashville retained first place by splitting a July 4 doubleheader with Atlanta before a crowd of over 3,000.<ref name=Bn7-4-94b>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47206912/lost-in-the-ninth/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Lost in the Ninth |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=July 4, 1894 |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |page=5}}</ref><ref name=Bn7-5-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47207714/a-very-close-shave/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=A Very Close Shave |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=July 5, 1894 |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |page=2}}</ref> Shaw was released on July 6.<ref name=Bn7-7-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47208387/played-two-games/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Played Two Games |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=July 7, 1894 |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |page=10}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Independence Day (United States)|Independence Day]] doubleheader was originally scheduled to be capped off by a [[night game]], but was prevented by rain.<ref name=Am7-5-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47208024/the-electric-light-game/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=The Electric Light Game |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=July 5, 1894 |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |page=6}}</ref> This was long before ballparks were equipped with electric lights, and night games were seen only as gimmicks. To put time into perspective, the first major league night game was not played until over 40&nbsp;years later in 1935.<ref name=Crosley>{{cite web|url=http://www.crosley-field.com/FNG/index.html|title=Night Baseball Arrives in the Majors|work=Crosley Field|accessdate=March 23, 2020|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090316053810/http://www.crosley-field.com/FNG/index.html|archivedate=March 16, 2009}}</ref> An attempt to play on July 5 was also rained out, but the spectacle was finally rescheduled for July 6 as a [[Doubleheader (baseball)#Tripleheaders|tripleheader]] against the New Orleans Pelicans. The first two games would be played during the afternoon, with the special night game to be played that evening at 8:30.<ref name=Am7-6-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47208150/three-games-to-day/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Three Games To-Day |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=July 6, 1894 |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |page=6}}</ref> \n\n[[File:George Harper 1894 night game.png|thumb|left|upright=1.1|alt=A black and white illustration of a baseball player wearing a dress with the ball held high over his head preparing to pitch|[[George Harper (pitcher)|George Harper]] pitched in a dress, wig, and bonnet for the [[night game]].<ref name=Am7-7-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47208541/was-no-end-of-fun/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Was No End of Fun |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=July 7, 1894 |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |page=6}}</ref>]]\n\nNew Orleans won the first game and Nashville won the second, allowing the Tigers to remain in first place.<ref name=Bn7-7-94/> The night game would be contested merely as an exhibition with all proceeds going to Nashville's players.<ref name=Am7-4-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47207376/to-days-great-programme/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=To-Day's Great Programme |work=The Daily American |location=Nashville |date=July 4, 1894 |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |page=6}}</ref> The special program commenced with a fireworks display and was followed by a balancing act and [[Slacklining|slack-wire walking]] demonstration. Members of both teams competed in long-distance throwing and sliding competitions and a {{convert|100|yd|adj=on}} dash won by Meara.<ref name=Bn7-7-94/> Fifty-four large electric lights were placed around Athletic Park to illuminate the field, and the [[baseball (ball)|baseball]] was covered with [[phosphorus]] to aid visibility.<ref name=Am7-4-94/> Adding to the novelty of a night game, players marched onto the field wearing burlesque costumes that included ballet outfits, loud suits, dresses, wigs, and bonnets.<ref name=Am7-7-94/> The estimated 4,000&nbsp;fans in attendance were entertained by antics such as base runners leading fielders on a chase through dark regions of the outfield and climbing up a light pole to avoid being tagged out.<ref name=Am7-7-94/><ref name=BT32>{{cite book |ref=harv |last=Traughber |first=Bill |date=2017 |title=Nashville Baseball History: From Sulphur Dell to the Sounds |location=South Orange, New Jersey |publisher=Summer Games Books|isbn=978-1-938545-83-2|page=23}}</ref> Nashville won, 3\u20132.<ref name=Am7-7-94/> This marked the first time that a night baseball game was played in Nashville, a feat often incorrectly attributed to the [[Nashville Vols]] in 1931, though the Vols' game was a serious contest.<ref name=BT32/>\n\nOn July 7, Nashville ended the opening homestand with a 15\u201311 victory over the Pelicans.<ref name=Bn7-9-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47208637/the-season-ended/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=The Season Ended |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=July 9, 1894 |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |page=5}}</ref> After the game, the team came to an abrupt end. Its demise, and eventually that of the Southern League, was caused when Memphis indicated it had no intention to play any more road games and the club sold two of its players to make up for recent financial losses, a violation of the league's rules.<ref name=At7-8-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47319272/on-its-last-legs/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=On Its Last Legs |work=The Atlanta Constitution |location=Atlanta |date=July 8, 1894 |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |page=16}}</ref> With the Nashvilles scheduled to play next in Memphis, rather than lay out the necessary capital for the three-city road trip with no guarantee that any of the clubs would return to play in Nashville, Stallings and Dooley payed their players' wages and disbanded.<ref name=Bn7-9-94/> As of their final game, the Tigers were in first place with a 6\u20133 (.667) record, half a game ahead of Atlanta.<ref name=Bn7-7-94/><ref name=Bn7-9-94/> Atlanta concluded its series at Memphis on July 8 with a win, thus tying for first with Nashville.<ref name=At7-9-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47220134/count-compau-comes/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Count Compau Comes |work=The Atlanta Constitution |location=Atlanta |date=July 9, 1894 |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |page=7}}</ref> New Orleans then traveled to Atlanta to close out the campaign by playing their final three scheduled games on July 10 and 11. Atlanta won all three, which moved them into first place and dropped the Tigers to second, {{frac|1|1|2}}&nbsp;games back.<ref name=Se7-13-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47318592/southern-baseball/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Southern Baseball |work=The Selma Times |location=Selma, Alabama |date=July 13, 1894 |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |page=2}}</ref> Nashville's composite record for both series was 30\u201337 (.448).<ref name=Bn6-28-94/><ref name=Bn7-7-94/><ref name=Bn7-9-94/>\n\nSeveral of the Nashvilles signed on with other teams, including Harper who was acquired by the National League's [[Philadelphia Phillies]].<ref name=Bn7-10-94>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47321673/the-nashville-players/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=The Nashville Players |work=Nashville Banner |location=Nashville |date=July 10, 1894 |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |page=3}}</ref> Some of the others stuck together to play two games on July 11 and 12 against a team from [[Clarksville, Tennessee|Clarksville]]. They had to pick up amateur players from the Nashville Athletic Club to make out a full lineup and lost both games.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47321513/we-win-again/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=We Win Again |work=The Leaf-Chronicle |location=Clarksville, Tennessee |date=July 12, 1894 |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |page=4}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47321558/again-victorious/ |via=Newspapers.com |title=Again Victorious |work=The Leaf-Chronicle |location=Clarksville, Tennessee |date=July 13, 1894 |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |page=4}}</ref> In 1895, the city was represented in the Southern League by the [[Nashville Seraphs]].<ref name=BRNashville/>\n\n== Season-by-season results ==\n=== 1893 standings ===\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-break}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+1893 Southern League first series standings (April 20\u2013July 4)<ref name=Reach1894/>\n!scope=\"col\" width=\"210px\" style=\"background-color:#ffffff; border-top:#d5d8cd 5px solid; border-bottom:#c41c1c 5px solid\"|Team\n!scope=\"col\" style=\"background-color:#ffffff; border-top:#d5d8cd 5px solid; border-bottom:#c41c1c 5px solid\"|Games\n!scope=\"col\" style=\"background-color:#ffffff; border-top:#d5d8cd 5px solid; border-bottom:#c41c1c 5px solid\"|Won\n!scope=\"col\" style=\"background-color:#ffffff; border-top:#d5d8cd 5px solid; border-bottom:#c41c1c 5px solid\"|Lost\n!scope=\"col\" style=\"background-color:#ffffff; border-top:#d5d8cd 5px solid; border-bottom:#c41c1c 5px solid\"|Win %\n!scope=\"col\" style=\"background-color:#ffffff; border-top:#d5d8cd 5px solid; border-bottom:#c41c1c 5px solid\"|Finish\n!scope=\"col\" style=\"background-color:#ffffff; border-top:#d5d8cd 5px solid; border-bottom:#c41c1c 5px solid\"|{{Abbr|GB|Games behind}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Augusta Electricians]]\n|61||44||17||.721||1st||\u2014\