e 2 = South African Weather Service<ref name=\"saws-climstats\">{{cite web \n|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120304032441/http://old.weathersa.co.za/Climat/Climstats/EastLondonStats.jsp\n|archivedate = 4 March 2012\n|url = http://old.weathersa.co.za/Climat/Climstats/EastLondonStats.jsp |title = Climate data for East London |accessdate = 7 March 2010 |publisher=South African Weather Service}}</ref>\n|date=August 2010\n}}\n</div>\n\n== Transport ==\nEast London is serviced by two national roads: the coastal [[N2 road (South Africa)|N2 highway]] connects it to [[King William's Town]], [[Port Elizabeth]] and [[Cape Town]] to the west and [[Mthatha]] and [[Durban]] to the east. It is the southern end of the [[N6 road (South Africa)|N6]], which runs north via [[Queenstown, Eastern Cape|Queenstown]] and [[Aliwal North]] to [[Bloemfontein]]. Older sections of the N2 have been renumbered the R102. The R72 is an alternative route to Port Elizabeth, via [[Port Alfred]]. The [[R346 road (South Africa)|R346]] is an alternative route to King William's Town. East London, like South Africa's other major cities, uses [[Metropolitan Routes in East London|Metropolitan]] (or M) routes as a third tier for its major intra-city roads.\n\n[[East London railway station]] offers long-distance passenger services to Cape Town and Johannesburg via Springfontein, and local services.\n\n[[East London Airport]] is a commercial airport with service to other large South African metropolitan areas.\n\n== Notable people ==\n{{sources|section|date=December 2018}}\n* [[Anthony Clifford Allison]] (1925\u20132014) was a South African geneticist and medical scientist, study on the genetic resistance to malaria<ref>{{cite web|title=Anthony Allison|url=http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/sfgate/obituary.aspx?pid=169878114|website=Legacy.com}}</ref>\n*[[Mark Andrews (rugby player)|Mark Andrews]] \u2013 Rugby player\n*[[Wendy Botha]] \u2013 Four-time world surfing champion\n*[[Mark Boucher]] \u2013 International cricketer\n*[[Vuyani Bungu]] \u2013 Boxer\n*[[Norman Catherine]] \u2013 Artist\n*[[Marjorie Courtenay-Latimer]] \u2013 Museum curator\n*[[The Dealians]] \u2013 Successful 1970s pop group\n*[[Allan Gray (investor)|Allan Gray]] \u2013 South African investor and philanthropist \n*[[Joan Harrison (swimmer)|Joan Harrison]] \u2013 Swimmer and 1952 Olympic champion\n*[[Rory Kockott]] \u2013 Rugby player\n*[[Welcome Ncita]] \u2013 Boxer\n*[[Makhaya Ntini]] \u2013 Test cricketer with over 100 caps for the [[South Africa national cricket team|South African national team]]\n*[[Steve Palframan]] \u2013 Cricketer\n*[[Ian Scheckter]] \u2013 Racing driver\n*[[Jody Scheckter]] \u2013 Formula 1 racing champion in 1979\n*[[Jonty Skinner]] \u2013 Swimmer and US swimming coach\n*[[John Gordon Sprigg]] \u2013 Prime Minister of the [[Cape Colony]]\n*[[Wayne Taylor]] \u2013 Racing driver\n*[[Andr\u00e9 Vos]] \u2013 Rugby player\n*[[Donald Woods]] \u2013 Author and anti-apartheid activist/born in Transkei\n*[[Jean-Michel Byron]] - Singer who sang with American rock band [[Toto (band)|Toto]] in the 1980s\n*[[Jacob Maliekal]] - National badminton player who represented South Africa at the Rio Olympic Games in 2016\n*[[Wouter Wessels]] - Senior FF+ politician\n\n==Coat of arms==\nThe East London municipality assumed a coat of arms on 29 August 1892.<ref name=el>Western Cape Archives : East London Municipal Minutes (29 August 1892)</ref><ref name=dd>''Daily Despatch'' (31 August 1892).</ref> The arms were : ''Argent, a cross Gules between in the first and fourth quarters a garb and in the second and third quarters a fleece Or; on a chief Azure a demi-sun Or.''  A golden anchor was placed behind the shield, no doubt to show that the town was a seaport.  The motto was ''Animo et fide''.\n\nThe arms were improved in the 1950s by the town clerk, H.H. Driffield.  He changed the shield from silver to ermine, removed the anchor and devised a crest consisting of two crossed anchors and a mural crown.  Heraldist [[Ivan Mitford-Barberton]] added two buffalo as supporters.<ref name=wca>Western Cape Archives : files 3/ELN 1587 (50/1151) and 1783 (1151/1).</ref> The improved design was granted by the [[College of Arms]] on 15 December 1959.  It was registered with the Cape Provincial Administration in 1960,<ref name=og>Cape of Good Hope ''Official Gazette'' 3040 (5 August 1960)</ref> and at the Bureau of Heraldry in 1967.<ref name=boh>{{Cite web|url=http://www.national.archsrch.gov.za/sm300cv/smws/sm300dl|title=National Archives of South Africa (NASA) Database Selection|website=www.national.archsrch.gov.za}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|East London, Eastern Cape}}\n* [http://www.buffalocity.gov.za Official website of Buffalo City]\n* {{Wikivoyage-inline|East London}}\n* [http://www.sahistory.org.za/places/east-london East London]\n\n{{Buffalo City Metropolitan Municipality}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Buffalo City Metropolitan Municipality]]\n[[Category:Populated coastal places in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Port cities in South Africa]]\n[[Category:East London, Eastern Cape| ]]\n[[Category:Second Boer War concentration camps]]\n[[Category:Port cities and towns of the Indian Ocean]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1872]]\n[[Category:1872 establishments in the Cape Colony]]\n[[Category:1872 establishments in South Africa]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toN1(link changed toN1 (South Africa)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/East_London,_Eastern_Cape"}
{"title_page": "Broadleaf weeds", "text_new": "{{Copyedit|date=April 2020}}\n'''Broadleaf weeds''' are unwanted pugnacious and tough plants that grow mostly around free areas in a lawn, garden or yard.<ref name=\"MISS\">{{cite news | last = | first =| title =Perennial Broadleaf Weeds in Lawns| newspaper =| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =missouribotanicalgarden.org| date = | url =http://www.missouribotanicalgarden.org/gardens-gardening/your-garden/help-for-the-home-gardener/advice-tips-resources/pests-and-problems/weeds/broadleaf-weeds.aspx | accessdate =30 May 2019}}</ref> They are often very easy to spot because they are different from normal grasses.<ref name=\"UPS\">{{cite news | last = | first =| title =Identify the weeds in your lawn and get rid of them| newspaper =| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =upscalelivingmag.com| date = | url =https://www.upscalelivingmag.com/identify-weeds-lawn-get-rid-good/ | accessdate =30 May 2019}}</ref> They  multiply with ease and can be very hard to control.<ref name=\"TUR\">{{cite news | last = | first =| title =5 Tips To Enhance Broadleaf Weed Control| newspaper =| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =turfmagazine.com| date = | url =https://www.turfmagazine.com/lawn-care/5-tips-to-enhance-broadleaf-weed-control/ | accessdate =30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Basic characteristics==\nBroadleaf weeds generally do not spring up in one specific pattern. Some of them are perennial in nature, others come up on an annual basis while others are biennial in nature. The perennial ones are often very difficult to control. They keep regenerating despite every effort to control them. The annual and biennial ones are easier to deal with. Looking at their visual nature, broadleaf weeds have wide leaves in common. They also have a main center vein that connects to smaller veins which shoot out from a branch. Despite this, they also differ in various  aspects.<ref name=\"MISS\"/>\n\nMost broadleaf weeds develop clusters of blossoms or single flowers as they mature. Such flowers are not aesthetic in nature. They often come in diverse colors such as white, blue, purple, red and so on. Some of them come with  mixed colored flowers while others bear single colored flowers. Despite this, they still appear  unruffled when clustered around a yard or lawn.\n\nThe roots of most broadleaf weeds are fibrous in nature. Some of them spring up with thin roots. Others spring up with a massive taproot while some of them spring up with both types of root systems.  A good number of broadleaf weeds spread through their seeds and rhizomes. Some of them only spread through seeds while others spread through seeds and rhizomes.<ref name=\"UPS\"/>\n\n==Common broadleaf weeds==\nThere are several types of broadleaf weeds  growing in lawns, gardens and yards across the globe.<ref>{{cite news | last = | first =| title =Broadleaf Weeds| newspaper =| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =plantscience.psu.edu| date = | url =https://plantscience.psu.edu/research/centers/turf/extension/plant-id/broadleaf | accessdate =30 May 2019}}</ref> Outlined below are the most common broadleaf weeds with their [[Binomial nomenclature|binomial names]]:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Common name !! Binomial name\n|-\n| Bramble|| ''Rubus spp.''\n|-\n| Butterfly-weed || ''Asclepias turberosa''\n|-\n| Chickweed, Common || ''Stallaria media L.''\n|-\n| Chickweed,\u00a0Mouse Ear\u00a0 || ''Cerastium vulgatum\u00a0L.''\n|-\n| Chicory || ''Cichorium intybus L.''\n|-\n| Clover || ''Trifolium repens''\n|-\n| Dandelion || ''Taraxacum officinale''\n|-\n| Dogfennel || ''Eupatorium capillifolium''\n|-\n| Jimsonweed || ''Datura stramonium''\n|-\n| Milkweed || ''Asclepias syriaca''\n|-\n| Prostrate knotweed || ''Polygonum aviculare''\n|-\n| Thistle Canada || ''Cirsium arvense''\n|-\n| Thistle,\u00a0Bull || ''Cirsium vulgare''\n|-\n| Violets || ''Viola papilonacea''\n|-\n|}\n\n==Brief descriptions of  common broadleaf weeds==\n===Brambles - ''Rubus spp.''===\n{{Main|Bramble}}\n[[Bramble]] is a common  perennial  broadleaf weed also known as ''Blackberries'' or ''Raspberries''. It grows in an erect form and propagates through its seeds, stolons and rhizomes. Brambles comes with coarsely serrated leaf margin with no leaf hairs. It also has alternate leaf arrangement. It has a taproot system with branching rhizome. Its flower is always white in color.<ref>{{cite news | last = | first =| title =Brambles Rubus spp.| newspaper =| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =plantscience.psu.edu| date = | url =https://plantscience.psu.edu/research/centers/turf/extension/plant-id/broadleaf/rubus | accessdate =30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Butterfly-weed - ''Asclepias turberosa''===\n{{Main|Asclepias tuberosa}}\nButterfly-weed  is also referred to as  ''Butterfly Milkweed'', ''Chiggar Weeds'', or ''Orange Milkweed''. It is a perennial type of broadleaf weed with clumsy growth habit. It spreads through its seeds and rhizomes. Butterfly-weed  comes with a large liner leaf structure with alternate leaf arrangement.  It has a woody rootstock root system and generates an orange colored flower.<ref>{{cite news | last = | first =| title =Butterfly-weed - Asclepias turberosa| newspaper =| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =plantscience.psu.edu| date = | url =https://plantscience.psu.edu/research/centers/turf/extension/plant-id/broadleaf/butterfly-weed | accessdate =30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Chickweed common -  Stallaria media L.===\n{{Main|Stellaria media}}\nChickweed common is also referred to as ''Alsine media'',\u00a0\u00a0''Alsine apetala'', ''Arenaria vulgaris'',\u00a0''Bindweed'', ''Chickenwort'', ''Craches'', ''Starweed'', ''Satin Flower'',\u00a0''Tongue-grass'' or ''Winterweed''. It comes as both perennial and annual type of broadleaf weed.  It has a prostrate growth habit and spreads through seed only. It  has a smooth leaf margin and egg-shaped leaf structure. It also has a shallow and fibrous root structure and bears a white colored flower.<ref name=\"plantscience.psu.edu\">{{cite news | last = | first =| title =Chickweed common - Stallaria media L| newspaper =| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =plantscience.psu.edu| date = | url =https://plantscience.psu.edu/research/centers/turf/extension/plant-id/broadleaf/common-chickweed | accessdate =30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Chickweed, Mouseear - ''Cerastium vulgatum\u00a0L''.===\n{{Main|Cerastium}}\nChickweed, Mouseear  is also known as ''Satin Flower'', ''Starweed'', ''Starwort'', ''Tongue Grass'' or ''Winter Weed''. It is a perennial type of broadleaf weed with a prostrate growth habit. It spreads by its seed.\nChickweed, Mouseear  comes with a smooth leaf margin and oval leaf structure. It has a fibrous root system and a bears  white colored flower.<ref name=\"plantscience.psu.edu\"/>\n\n===Chicory - ''Cichorium intybus L''.===\n{{Main|Chicory}}\nChicory  is also referred to as  ''Blue Succory'', ''Coffee-weed'' or ''Common Chicory''. It is a typical perennial broadleaf weed that spreads through its seed. It grows in an erect stem with a coarse leaf margin and irregular lobes. It has a dark brown taproot system and generates a blue colored flower.<ref>{{cite news | last = | first =| title =Chicory - Cichorium intybus L| newspaper =| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =plantscience.psu.edu| date = | url =https://plantscience.psu.edu/research/centers/turf/extension/plant-id/broadleaf/chicory | accessdate =30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Clover - ''Trifolium repens''===\n{{Main|Trifolium repens}}\nClover is also known as ''Dutch Clover'', ''Purple Dutch Clover'' or ''Shamrock''. It is a perennial type of broadleaf weed with a prostrate growth habit. It spreads through its solons and seed. It has smallish leaf with teeth and egg-shaped leaf structure alongside alternate leaf arrangement.  It also has a fibrous root system and bears white and pink colored flower.<ref>{{cite news | last = | first =| title =Clover - Trifolium repens| newspaper =| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =plantscience.psu.edu| date = | url =https://plantscience.psu.edu/research/centers/turf/extension/plant-id/broadleaf/white-clover | accessdate =30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Dandelion - ''Taraxacum officinale''===\n{{Main|Taraxacum}}\nDandelion is also referred to as  ''Lions Tooth'' or ''Blow-ball''. It is a perennial type of broadleaf weed that spreads through its seeds and taproots. It has a coarse leaf margin with alternate leaf arrangement.  It also has a thick and long taproot system and has a yellowish flower.<ref>{{cite news | last = | first =| title =Dandelion - Taraxacum officinale| newspaper =| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =plantscience.psu.edu| date = | url =https://plantscience.psu.edu/research/centers/turf/extension/plant-id/broadleaf/dandelion | accessdate =30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Dogfennel - ''Eupatorium capillifolium''===\n{{Main|Eupatorium capillifolium}}\nDogfennel is also known as ''Dog's Fennel'' or\u00a0''Eupatorium faoeiculaceum''. It is a perennial type of broadleaf week with an erect growth habit. It spreads through its seed. It comes with serrated leaf margin, dissected leaf structure and alternate leaf arrangement. It also has a fibrous root system and bears a greenish white flower.<ref>{{cite news | last = | first =| title =Dogfennel - Eupatorium capillifolium| newspaper =| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =plantscience.psu.edu| date = | url =https://plantscience.psu.edu/research/centers/turf/extension/plant-id/broadleaf/dog-fennel | accessdate =30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Jimsonweed - ''Datura stramonium''===\n{{Main|Datura stramonium}}\nJimsonweed is also known as ''Jamestown-weed'' or ''Mad-apple''. It is an annual type of  broadleaf weed with a heavily bracketed and erect growth habit. It spreads through its seed and bears a white or purple flower.  It come with a wide leaf margin and alternate leaf arrangement. It also has a shallow taproot system.<ref>{{cite news | last = | first =| title =Jimsonweed - Datura stramonium| newspaper =| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =plantscience.psu.edu| date = | url =https://plantscience.psu.edu/research/centers/turf/extension/plant-id/broadleaf/jimson | accessdate =30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Milkweed - ''Asclepias syriaca''===\n{{Main|Asclepias}}\nMilkweed is also known as  ''Cottong-weed'' or ''Silkweed''. It is a perennial type of broadleaf weed with an erect growth habit. It propagates through its seed and bears purple, pink or white flower.  It comes with smooth leaf margin and opposite leaf arrangement. Its root type is fleshy roots and rhizomes.<ref>{{cite news | last = | first =| title =Milkweed - Asclepias syriaca| newspaper =| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =plantscience.psu.edu| date = | url =https://plantscience.psu.edu/research/centers/turf/extension/plant-id/broadleaf/milkweed | accessdate =30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Prostrate knotweed - ''Polygonum aviculare''===\n{{Main|Polygonum aviculare}}\nProstrate knotweed is also known as ''Door-weed'', ''Knot-grass'' or ''Mat-grass''. It is an annual type of broadleaf week with a prostrate growth habit. It propagates through its seed and bears white, green or pink flowers. It comes with smooth leaf margin with alternate leaf arrangement. It also has a taproot system.<ref>{{cite news | last = | first =| title =Prostrate knotweed - Polygonum aviculare| newspaper =| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =plantscience.psu.edu| date = | url =https://plantscience.psu.edu/research/centers/turf/extension/plant-id/broadleaf/prostrate-knotweed | accessdate =30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Thistle Canada - ''Cirsium arvense''===\n{{Main|Cirsium arvense}}\nThistle Canada\tis also referred to as ''creeping thistle'' or ''small-flowered thistle''. It is a perennial type of broadleaf weed with an erect growth habit.  It spreads through its seeds and rhizomes. it also pears pink or purple flowers.  The weed comes with alternate leaf arrangement and has an extensive rhizomes root type.<ref>{{cite news | last = | first =| title =Thistle Canada - Cirsium arvense| newspaper =| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =plantscience.psu.edu| date = | url =https://plantscience.psu.edu/research/centers/turf/extension/plant-id/broadleaf/canada-thistle | accessdate =30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Thistle bull, ''Cirsium vulgare''===\n{{Main|Cirsium vulgare}}\nThistle Bull  is also known as ''thistle'' or ''sprear''. It is a biennial type of broadleaf weed with a basal rosette growth habit.  It spreads through its seeds and bears red or purple flower. It comes with an alternate leaf arrangement and has a taproot with secondary fibrous root system.<ref>{{cite news | last = | first =| title =Thistle Bull, Cirsium vulgare| newspaper =| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =plantscience.psu.edu| date = | url =https://plantscience.psu.edu/research/centers/turf/extension/plant-id/broadleaf/bull-thistle | accessdate =30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Violets - ''Viola papilonacea''===\n{{Main|Viola (plant)}}\nViolets are also referred to as the ''hooded blue violet'' or ''meadow-violet''.  It is a typical example of perennial broadleaf weed that spreads with ease.  It propagates through its seeds or rhizomes and bears blue or purple flower. It comes with heart-shaped leaf structure and a coarse root system.<ref>{{cite news | last = | first =| title =Violets - Viola papilonace| newspaper =| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =plantscience.psu.edu| date = | url =https://plantscience.psu.edu/research/centers/turf/extension/plant-id/broadleaf/violet | accessdate =30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Contrast with other types of weeds==\nThe differences in broadleaf weeds structure and their  growth habits make them easy to be distinguished from grasses.  Generally, most common weed plants  belong to one of two weed families namely, ''broadleaf (dicotyledon)'' or ''narrow leaf (monocotyledon)''.  Broadleaf  weeds grow from  tap roots or fibrous root systems and have larger leaves.  Narrow leaf weeds are also referred to as grasses.  They have fibrous roots systems and long narrow leaves.<ref>{{cite news | last =Tilley | first =Nikki | title =What Is A Weed: Weed Info And Control Methods In The Garden\n| newspaper =| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =gardeningknowhow.com| date = | url =https://www.gardeningknowhow.com/plant-problems/weeds/what-is-a-weed.htm | accessdate =30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nMost broadleaf weeds have leaves with net-like veins.  They also have  nodes that contain one or more leaves.  They may have showy flowers.  On the other hand, narrow weeds or grasses do not have net-like veins and nodes that contain more leaves.  They can be flat in nature.  Moreover, broadleaf weed have seedlings that come up with two leaves.  This is not the case with grasses that can easily spring up at any given time.<ref>{{cite news | last = | first =| title =Broadleaf Weeds| newspaper =| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =hgic.clemson.edu| date = | url =https://hgic.clemson.edu/factsheet/broadleaf-weeds/| accessdate =30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nFurthermore, grassy weeds  are so called because they spring up as desirable grasses.{{Clarify|date=April 2020}}  This makes them very hard to be identified when comparing them with broadleaf weeds.  Grassy weed  come up with blades which showcase as a single leaf from a germinated grass seed.  This makes them quite different from broadleaf weeds especially in appearance.<ref>{{cite news | last = | first =| title =The Differences Between Broadleaf and Grassy Weeds| newspaper =| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =cardinallawns.com| date =7 July 2016 | url =https://www.cardinallawns.com/2016/07/differences-between-broadleaf-grassy-weeds/| accessdate =30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Methods of controlling==\nAlthough broadleaf weeds  are known to be aggressive and tough in nature, they can still be controlled. The gardens, yards and lawns are the most common place they thrive.  There are several ways of controlling them.<ref name=\"NEWS\">{{cite news | last =Trapp | first =Abby | title =Plan a strategy for weed control |work=News-Press NOW |date=28 May 2019 | url =http://www.newspressnow.com/news/local_news/plan-a-strategy-for-weed-control/article_d6d4f086-7db5-11e9-8117-833bed713e1d.html| accessdate =30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Detecting their growth cycle===\n{{Clarify section|date=April 2020}}\nOne of the best ways of dealing with broadleaf weeds is to detect their growth cycle.  This requires proper monitoring.  Most  plants experts use this method since it has been proven to be the most effective.  It involves discovering how  broadleaf weeds grow and depriving them on that growth cycle.<ref name=\"SC\">{{cite web |title=Learn more about Broadleaf Weeds |website=sciencedirect.com |url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/agricultural-and-biological-sciences/broadleaf-weeds |access-date=30 May 2019}}{{Unreliable source?|date=December 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Using a weed killer===\nIn situations where there are massive growth of broadleaf weeds, using a good weed killer can be very helpful.  This is usually the case for lawns or  yards that are overgrown with such weeds. There are several good weed killers available in the market.  It is also important to seek the advice of a  weed plant expert  when looking for a weed killer.<ref name=\"NEWS\"/>\n\n===Hand-picking===\nIn lawns, gardens or yards where there are few broadleaf weeds present, the best approach to use is hand-pulling.  This should be carried out from time to time in order to check the spread weeds.<ref name=\"SC\"/>\n\n===Lawn mowing===\nIn a thick lawn that is overgrown with broadleaf weeds, the lawn moving method is considered the best approach.  This involves the use of a lawn mower in uprooting the weed.  It can be very tedious especially in situations where there are massive growth of the broadleaf weeds.<ref name=\"TUR\"/>\n\n===Use of chemical herbicides===\nThere are chemical herbicides meant for controlling broadleaf weeds.  The use of such chemicals is often the best option when thinking of clearing the entire yard or lawn of all manner of weeds.  In most cases, the chemical content prevent the weeds from re-surfacing for several months.   The perennial types of broadleaf weeds are often controlled with chemical herbicides although they still find their way back after some months  especially when the cleared lawn or yard is  left unused for months.<ref>{{cite news |title=Broadleaf Weed Problems in Lawns |website=LawnTalk |publisher=University of Illinois Extension |url=https://extension.illinois.edu/lawntalk/weeds/broadleaf_weed_problems_in_lawns.cfm |access-date=30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Shading out===\nBroadleaf weeds can be controlled by shading them out.  This involves covering the entire affected area with flat materials such as boards, nylon, plastic spread,  and the like.  When broadleaf weeds are covered that way, they lack access to sunlight and rain that speed up their growth. By so doing, they wither away.<ref name=\"TUR\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Weed]]\n* [[List of common weeds of Queensland]]\n* [[Weed control]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n\n\n[[Category:Garden pests]]\n[[Category:Plants and humans]]\n[[Category:Agricultural pests]]\n", "text_old": "{{Copyedit|date=April 2020}}\n'''Broadleaf weeds''' are unwanted pugnacious and tough plants that grow mostly around free areas in a lawn, garden or yard.<ref name=\"MISS\">{{cite news | last = | first =| title =Perennial Broadleaf Weeds in Lawns| newspaper =| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =missouribotanicalgarden.org| date = | url =http://www.missouribotanicalgarden.org/gardens-gardening/your-garden/help-for-the-home-gardener/advice-tips-resources/pests-and-problems/weeds/broadleaf-weeds.aspx | accessdate =30 May 2019}}</ref> They are often very easy to spot because they are different from normal grasses.<ref name=\"UPS\">{{cite news | last = | first =| title =Identify the weeds in your lawn and get rid of them| newspaper =| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =upscalelivingmag.com| date = | url =https://www.upscalelivingmag.com/identify-weeds-lawn-get-rid-good/ | accessdate =30 May 2019}}</ref> They  multiply with ease and can be very hard to control.<ref name=\"TUR\">{{cite news | last = | first =| title =5 Tips To Enhance Broadleaf Weed Control| newspaper =| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =turfmagazine.com| date = | url =https://www.turfmagazine.com/lawn-care/5-tips-to-enhance-broadleaf-weed-control/ | accessdate =30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Basic characteristics==\nBroadleaf weeds generally do not spring up in one specific pattern. Some of them are perennial in nature, others come up on an annual basis while others are biennial in nature. The perennial ones are often very difficult to control. They keep regenerating despite every effort to control them. The annual and biennial ones are easier to deal with. Looking at their visual nature, broadleaf weeds have wide leaves in common. They also have a main center vein that connects to smaller veins which shoot out from a branch. Despite this, they also differ in various  aspects.<ref name=\"MISS\"/>\n\nMost broadleaf weeds develop clusters of blossoms or single flowers as they mature. Such flowers are not aesthetic in nature. They often come in diverse colors such as white, blue, purple, red and so on. Some of them come with  mixed colored flowers while others bear single colored flowers. Despite this, they still appear  unruffled when clustered around a yard or lawn.\n\nThe roots of most broadleaf weeds are fibrous in nature. Some of them spring up with thin roots. Others spring up with a massive taproot while some of them spring up with both types of root systems.  A good number of broadleaf weeds spread through their seeds and rhizomes. Some of them only spread through seeds while others spread through seeds and rhizomes.<ref name=\"UPS\"/>\n\n==Common broadleaf weeds==\nThere are several types of broadleaf weeds  growing in lawns, gardens and yards across the globe.<ref>{{cite news | last = | first =| title =Broadleaf Weeds| newspaper =| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =plantscience.psu.edu| date = | url =https://plantscience.psu.edu/research/centers/turf/extension/plant-id/broadleaf | accessdate =30 May 2019}}</ref> Outlined below are the most common broadleaf weeds with their [[Binomial nomenclature|binomial names]]:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Common name !! Binomial name\n|-\n| Bramble|| ''Rubus spp.''\n|-\n| Butterfly-weed || ''Asclepias turberosa''\n|-\n| Chickweed, Common || ''Stallaria media L.''\n|-\n| Chickweed,\u00a0Mouse Ear\u00a0 || ''Cerastium vulgatum\u00a0L.''\n|-\n| Chicory || ''Cichorium intybus L.''\n|-\n| Clover || ''Trifolium repens''\n|-\n| Dandelion || ''Taraxacum officinale''\n|-\n| Dogfennel || ''Eupatorium capillifolium''\n|-\n| Jimsonweed || ''Datura stramonium''\n|-\n| Milkweed || ''Asclepias syriaca''\n|-\n| Prostrate knotweed || ''Polygonum aviculare''\n|-\n| Thistle Canada || ''Cirsium arvense''\n|-\n| Thistle,\u00a0Bull || ''Cirsium vulgare''\n|-\n| Violets || ''Viola papilonacea''\n|-\n|}\n\n==Brief descriptions of  common broadleaf weeds==\n===Brambles - ''Rubus spp.''===\n{{Main|Bramble}}\n[[Bramble]] is a common  perennial  broadleaf weed also known as ''Blackberries'' or ''Raspberries''. It grows in an erect form and propagates through its seeds, stolons and rhizomes. Brambles comes with coarsely serrated leaf margin with no leaf hairs. It also has alternate leaf arrangement. It has a taproot system with branching rhizome. Its flower is always white in color.<ref>{{cite news | last = | first =| title =Brambles Rubus spp.| newspaper =| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =plantscience.psu.edu| date = | url =https://plantscience.psu.edu/research/centers/turf/extension/plant-id/broadleaf/rubus | accessdate =30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Butterfly-weed - ''Asclepias turberosa''===\n{{Main|Asclepias tuberosa}}\nButterfly-weed  is also referred to as  ''Butterfly Milkweed'', ''Chiggar Weeds'', or ''Orange Milkweed''. It is a perennial type of broadleaf weed with clumsy growth habit. It spreads through its seeds and rhizomes. Butterfly-weed  comes with a large liner leaf structure with alternate leaf arrangement.  It has a woody rootstock root system and generates an orange colored flower.<ref>{{cite news | last = | first =| title =Butterfly-weed - Asclepias turberosa| newspaper =| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =plantscience.psu.edu| date = | url =https://plantscience.psu.edu/research/centers/turf/extension/plant-id/broadleaf/butterfly-weed | accessdate =30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Chickweed common -  Stallaria media L.===\n{{Main|Stellaria media}}\nChickweed common is also referred to as ''Alsine media'',\u00a0\u00a0''Alsine apetala'', ''Arenaria vulgaris'',\u00a0''Bindweed'', ''Chickenwort'', ''Craches'', ''Starweed'', ''Satin Flower'',\u00a0''Tongue-grass'' or ''Winterweed''. It comes as both perennial and annual type of broadleaf weed.  It has a prostrate growth habit and spreads through seed only. It  has smooth leaf margin and egg-shaped leaf structure. It also has a shallow and fibrous root structure and bears a white colored flower.<ref name=\"plantscience.psu.edu\">{{cite news | last = | first =| title =Chickweed common - Stallaria media L| newspaper =| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =plantscience.psu.edu| date = | url =https://plantscience.psu.edu/research/centers/turf/extension/plant-id/broadleaf/common-chickweed | accessdate =30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Chickweed, Mouseear - ''Cerastium vulgatum\u00a0L''.===\n{{Main|Cerastium}}\nChickweed, Mouseear  is also known as ''Satin Flower'', ''Starweed'', ''Starwort'', ''Tongue Grass'' or ''Winter Weed''. It is a perennial type of broadleaf weed with a prostrate growth habit. It spreads by its seed.\nChickweed, Mouseear  comes with a smooth leaf margin and oval leaf structure. It has a fibrous root system and a bears  white colored flower.<ref name=\"plantscience.psu.edu\"/>\n\n===Chicory - ''Cichorium intybus L''.===\n{{Main|Chicory}}\nChicory  is also referred to as  ''Blue Succory'', ''Coffee-weed'' or ''Common Chicory''. It is a typical perennial broadleaf weed that spreads through its seed. It grows in an erect stem with a coarse leaf margin and irregular lobes. It has a dark brown taproot system and generates a blue colored flower.<ref>{{cite news | last = | first =| title =Chicory - Cichorium intybus L| newspaper =| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =plantscience.psu.edu| date = | url =https://plantscience.psu.edu/research/centers/turf/extension/plant-id/broadleaf/chicory | accessdate =30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Clover - ''Trifolium repens''===\n{{Main|Trifolium repens}}\nClover is also known as ''Dutch Clover'', ''Purple Dutch Clover'' or ''Shamrock''. It is a perennial type of broadleaf weed with a prostrate growth habit. It spreads through its solons and seed. It has smallish leaf with teeth and egg-shaped leaf structure alongside alternate leaf arrangement.  It also has a fibrous root system and bears white and pink colored flower.<ref>{{cite news | last = | first =| title =Clover - Trifolium repens| newspaper =| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =plantscience.psu.edu| date = | url =https://plantscience.psu.edu/research/centers/turf/extension/plant-id/broadleaf/white-clover | accessdate =30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Dandelion - ''Taraxacum officinale''===\n{{Main|Taraxacum}}\nDandelion is also referred to as  ''Lions Tooth'' or ''Blow-ball''. It is a perennial type of broadleaf weed that spreads through its seeds and taproots. It has a coarse leaf margin with alternate leaf arrangement.  It also has a thick and long taproot system and has a yellowish flower.<ref>{{cite news | last = | first =| title =Dandelion - Taraxacum officinale| newspaper =| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =plantscience.psu.edu| date = | url =https://plantscience.psu.edu/research/centers/turf/extension/plant-id/broadleaf/dandelion | accessdate =30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Dogfennel - ''Eupatorium capillifolium''===\n{{Main|Eupatorium capillifolium}}\nDogfennel is also known as ''Dog's Fennel'' or\u00a0''Eupatorium faoeiculaceum''. It is a perennial type of broadleaf week with an erect growth habit. It spreads through its seed. It comes with serrated leaf margin, dissected leaf structure and alternate leaf arrangement. It also has a fibrous root system and bears a greenish white flower.<ref>{{cite news | last = | first =| title =Dogfennel - Eupatorium capillifolium| newspaper =| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =plantscience.psu.edu| date = | url =https://plantscience.psu.edu/research/centers/turf/extension/plant-id/broadleaf/dog-fennel | accessdate =30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Jimsonweed - ''Datura stramonium''===\n{{Main|Datura stramonium}}\nJimsonweed is also known as ''Jamestown-weed'' or ''Mad-apple''. It is an annual type of  broadleaf weed with a heavily bracketed and erect growth habit. It spreads through its seed and bears a white or purple flower.  It come with a wide leaf margin and alternate leaf arrangement. It also has a shallow taproot system.<ref>{{cite news | last = | first =| title =Jimsonweed - Datura stramonium| newspaper =| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =plantscience.psu.edu| date = | url =https://plantscience.psu.edu/research/centers/turf/extension/plant-id/broadleaf/jimson | accessdate =30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Milkweed - ''Asclepias syriaca''===\n{{Main|Asclepias}}\nMilkweed is also known as  ''Cottong-weed'' or ''Silkweed''. It is a perennial type of broadleaf weed with an erect growth habit. It propagates through its seed and bears purple, pink or white flower.  It comes with smooth leaf margin and opposite leaf arrangement. Its root type is fleshy roots and rhizomes.<ref>{{cite news | last = | first =| title =Milkweed - Asclepias syriaca| newspaper =| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =plantscience.psu.edu| date = | url =https://plantscience.psu.edu/research/centers/turf/extension/plant-id/broadleaf/milkweed | accessdate =30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Prostrate knotweed - ''Polygonum aviculare''===\n{{Main|Polygonum aviculare}}\nProstrate knotweed is also known as ''Door-weed'', ''Knot-grass'' or ''Mat-grass''. It is an annual type of broadleaf week with a prostrate growth habit. It propagates through its seed and bears white, green or pink flowers. It comes with smooth leaf margin with alternate leaf arrangement. It also has a taproot system.<ref>{{cite news | last = | first =| title =Prostrate knotweed - Polygonum aviculare| newspaper =| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =plantscience.psu.edu| date = | url =https://plantscience.psu.edu/research/centers/turf/extension/plant-id/broadleaf/prostrate-knotweed | accessdate =30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Thistle Canada - ''Cirsium arvense''===\n{{Main|Cirsium arvense}}\nThistle Canada\tis also referred to as ''creeping thistle'' or ''small-flowered thistle''. It is a perennial type of broadleaf weed with an erect growth habit.  It spreads through its seeds and rhizomes. it also pears pink or purple flowers.  The weed comes with alternate leaf arrangement and has an extensive rhizomes root type.<ref>{{cite news | last = | first =| title =Thistle Canada - Cirsium arvense| newspaper =| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =plantscience.psu.edu| date = | url =https://plantscience.psu.edu/research/centers/turf/extension/plant-id/broadleaf/canada-thistle | accessdate =30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Thistle bull, ''Cirsium vulgare''===\n{{Main|Cirsium vulgare}}\nThistle Bull  is also known as ''thistle'' or ''sprear''. It is a biennial type of broadleaf weed with a basal rosette growth habit.  It spreads through its seeds and bears red or purple flower. It comes with an alternate leaf arrangement and has a taproot with secondary fibrous root system.<ref>{{cite news | last = | first =| title =Thistle Bull, Cirsium vulgare| newspaper =| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =plantscience.psu.edu| date = | url =https://plantscience.psu.edu/research/centers/turf/extension/plant-id/broadleaf/bull-thistle | accessdate =30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Violets - ''Viola papilonacea''===\n{{Main|Viola (plant)}}\nViolets are also referred to as the ''hooded blue violet'' or ''meadow-violet''.  It is a typical example of perennial broadleaf weed that spreads with ease.  It propagates through its seeds or rhizomes and bears blue or purple flower. It comes with heart-shaped leaf structure and a coarse root system.<ref>{{cite news | last = | first =| title =Violets - Viola papilonace| newspaper =| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =plantscience.psu.edu| date = | url =https://plantscience.psu.edu/research/centers/turf/extension/plant-id/broadleaf/violet | accessdate =30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Contrast with other types of weeds==\nThe differences in broadleaf weeds structure and their  growth habits make them easy to be distinguished from grasses.  Generally, most common weed plants  belong to one of two weed families namely, ''broadleaf (dicotyledon)'' or ''narrow leaf (monocotyledon)''.  Broadleaf  weeds grow from  tap roots or fibrous root systems and have larger leaves.  Narrow leaf weeds are also referred to as grasses.  They have fibrous roots systems and long narrow leaves.<ref>{{cite news | last =Tilley | first =Nikki | title =What Is A Weed: Weed Info And Control Methods In The Garden\n| newspaper =| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =gardeningknowhow.com| date = | url =https://www.gardeningknowhow.com/plant-problems/weeds/what-is-a-weed.htm | accessdate =30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nMost broadleaf weeds have leaves with net-like veins.  They also have  nodes that contain one or more leaves.  They may have showy flowers.  On the other hand, narrow weeds or grasses do not have net-like veins and nodes that contain more leaves.  They can be flat in nature.  Moreover, broadleaf weed have seedlings that come up with two leaves.  This is not the case with grasses that can easily spring up at any given time.<ref>{{cite news | last = | first =| title =Broadleaf Weeds| newspaper =| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =hgic.clemson.edu| date = | url =https://hgic.clemson.edu/factsheet/broadleaf-weeds/| accessdate =30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nFurthermore, grassy weeds  are so called because they spring up as desirable grasses.{{Clarify|date=April 2020}}  This makes them very hard to be identified when comparing them with broadleaf weeds.  Grassy weed  come up with blades which showcase as a single leaf from a germinated grass seed.  This makes them quite different from broadleaf weeds especially in appearance.<ref>{{cite news | last = | first =| title =The Differences Between Broadleaf and Grassy Weeds| newspaper =| location = | pages = | language = | publisher =cardinallawns.com| date =7 July 2016 | url =https://www.cardinallawns.com/2016/07/differences-between-broadleaf-grassy-weeds/| accessdate =30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Methods of controlling==\nAlthough broadleaf weeds  are known to be aggressive and tough in nature, they can still be controlled. The gardens, yards and lawns are the most common place they thrive.  There are several ways of controlling them.<ref name=\"NEWS\">{{cite news | last =Trapp | first =Abby | title =Plan a strategy for weed control |work=News-Press NOW |date=28 May 2019 | url =http://www.newspressnow.com/news/local_news/plan-a-strategy-for-weed-control/article_d6d4f086-7db5-11e9-8117-833bed713e1d.html| accessdate =30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Detecting their growth cycle===\n{{Clarify section|date=April 2020}}\nOne of the best ways of dealing with broadleaf weeds is to detect their growth cycle.  This requires proper monitoring.  Most  plants experts use this method since it has been proven to be the most effective.  It involves discovering how  broadleaf weeds grow and depriving them on that growth cycle.<ref name=\"SC\">{{cite web |title=Learn more about Broadleaf Weeds |website=sciencedirect.com |url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/agricultural-and-biological-sciences/broadleaf-weeds |access-date=30 May 2019}}{{Unreliable source?|date=December 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Using a weed killer===\nIn situations where there are massive growth of broadleaf weeds, using a good weed killer can be very helpful.  This is usually the case for lawns or  yards that are overgrown with such weeds. There are several good weed killers available in the market.  It is also important to seek the advice of a  weed plant expert  when looking for a weed killer.<ref name=\"NEWS\"/>\n\n===Hand-picking===\nIn lawns, gardens or yards where there are few broadleaf weeds present, the best approach to use is hand-pulling.  This should be carried out from time to time in order to check the spread weeds.<ref name=\"SC\"/>\n\n===Lawn mowing===\nIn a thick lawn that is overgrown with broadleaf weeds, the lawn moving method is considered the best approach.  This involves the use of a lawn mower in uprooting the weed.  It can be very tedious especially in situations where there are massive growth of the broadleaf weeds.<ref name=\"TUR\"/>\n\n===Use of chemical herbicides===\nThere are chemical herbicides meant for controlling broadleaf weeds.  The use of such chemicals is often the best option when thinking of clearing the entire yard or lawn of all manner of weeds.  In most cases, the chemical content prevent the weeds from re-surfacing for several months.   The perennial types of broadleaf weeds are often controlled with chemical herbicides although they still find their way back after some months  especially when the cleared lawn or yard is  left unused for months.<ref>{{cite news |title=Broadleaf Weed Problems in Lawns |website=LawnTalk |publisher=University of Illinois Extension |url=https://extension.illinois.edu/lawntalk/weeds/broadleaf_weed_problems_in_lawns.cfm |access-date=30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Shading out===\nBroadleaf weeds can be controlled by shading them out.  This involves covering the entire affected area with flat materials such as boards, nylon, plastic spread,  and the like.  When broadleaf weeds are covered that way, they lack access to sunlight and rain that speed up their growth. By so doing, they wither away.<ref name=\"TUR\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Weed]]\n* [[List of common weeds of Queensland]]\n* [[Weed control]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n\n\n[[Category:Garden pests]]\n[[Category:Plants and humans]]\n[[Category:Agricultural pests]]\n", "name_user": "Llunnaz", "label": "safe", "comment": "added article", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Broadleaf_weeds"}
{"title_page": "Pet Food Express", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2011}}\n{{coord|37.73929|-122.19208|type:landmark_region:US-CA|display=title}}\n{{multiple issues\n|{{Notability|Companies|date=March 2010}}\n{{more citations needed|date=March 2010}}\n{{primary sources|date=March 2010}}\n}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name       = Pet Food Express\n| logo       = Pet Food Express.svg\n| logo_size  = 200px\n| type       = Private company\n| genre      = Pet store\n| foundation = 1986\n| location   = 500, 85th Avenue<br>[[Oakland, California|Oakland]], California\n| industry   = Retail\n| products   = Pet supplies\n| owner      = Michael Levy<br>Mark Witriol\n| homepage   = {{url|petfoodexpress.com}}\n}}  \n'''Pet Food Express''' is a [[California]] chain of [[retail store]]s that offers pet food, with a focus on premium brands, [[Holistic health|holistic]], and [[Organic food|organic]] pet food, as well as other pet supplies, and self-service dog washing facilities.<ref>http://petfoodexpress.com/products/pet-wash/</ref> \nPet Food Express President and co-owner Michael Levy started a [[dog training]] business in 1976 and opened his first San Francisco location in 1980, selling some food and supplies. In 1986, he left dog training to focus on retail and had expanded to three locations by the time his business partner, Mark Witriol, came aboard in 1992. They have since expanded, even during the recent recession, and have 54 locations in Northern California, with 9 more in Southern California. Levy and Pet Food Express partner with more than 100 non-profit [[Rescue group|animal rescue]] and shelter organizations, and regularly donate more than $1 million a year to those organizations. The company set up cat adoption centers in its stores starting in 2011 and claims that approximately 1,000 cats have been adopted through its [[California]] stores since the program's inception.<ref>{{cite web|last=Harmanci|first=Reyhan|title=San Francisco Teams with Pet Supply Stores on Cat Adoptions|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/04/01/us/san-francisco-teams-with-pet-supply-stores-on-cat-adoptions.html|publisher=The New York Times|accessdate=5 April 2012}}</ref> Pet Food Express has a high standard of quality for its food and products. The company motto is: \"If we won't feed it to our pets, we won't sell it for yours.\"\n\n__TOC__\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://petfoodexpress.com}}\n* [http://www.petfoodexpressadoptions.com Pet Food Express Adoptions]\n* {http://www.petconearme1.com/ Petco Guider for Animal Foods}\n\n{{Pet stores}}\n\n[[Category:American companies established in 1986]]\n[[Category:Retail companies established in 1986]]\n[[Category:Online retailers of the United States]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Oakland, California]]\n[[Category:Pet stores]]\n[[Category:1986 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Retail companies based in California]]\n[[Category:Pets in the United States]]\n[[Category:Food and drink companies based in California]]\n\n{{US-retail-company-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2011}}\n{{coord|37.73929|-122.19208|type:landmark_region:US-CA|display=title}}\n{{multiple issues\n|{{Notability|Companies|date=March 2010}}\n{{more citations needed|date=March 2010}}\n{{primary sources|date=March 2010}}\n}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name       = Pet Food Express\n| logo       = Pet Food Express.svg\n| logo_size  = 200px\n| type       = Private company\n| genre      = Pet store\n| foundation = 1986\n| location   = 500, 85th Avenue<br>[[Oakland, California|Oakland]], California\n| industry   = Retail\n| products   = Pet supplies\n| owner      = Michael Levy<br>Mark Witriol\n| homepage   = {{url|petfoodexpress.com}}\n}}  \n'''Pet Food Express''' is a [[California]] chain of [[retail store]]s that offers pet food, with a focus on premium brands, [[Holistic health|holistic]], and [[Organic food|organic]] pet food, as well as other pet supplies, and self-service dog washing facilities.<ref>http://petfoodexpress.com/products/pet-wash/</ref> \nPet Food Express President and co-owner Michael Levy started a [[dog training]] business in 1976 and opened his first San Francisco location in 1980, selling some food and supplies. In 1986, he left dog training to focus on retail and had expanded to three locations by the time his business partner, Mark Witriol, came aboard in 1992. They have since expanded, even during the recent recession, and have 54 locations in Northern California, with 9 more in Southern California. Levy and Pet Food Express partner with more than 100 non-profit [[Rescue group|animal rescue]] and shelter organizations, and regularly donate more than $1 million a year to those organizations. The company set up cat adoption centers in its stores starting in 2011 and claims that approximately 1,000 cats have been adopted through its [[California]] stores since the program's inception.<ref>{{cite web|last=Harmanci|first=Reyhan|title=San Francisco Teams with Pet Supply Stores on Cat Adoptions|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/04/01/us/san-francisco-teams-with-pet-supply-stores-on-cat-adoptions.html|publisher=The New York Times|accessdate=5 April 2012}}</ref> Pet Food Express has a high standard of quality for its food and products. The company motto is: \"If we won't feed it to our pets, we won't sell it for yours.\"\n\n__TOC__\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://petfoodexpress.com}}\n* [http://www.petfoodexpressadoptions.com Pet Food Express Adoptions]\n\n{{Pet stores}}\n\n[[Category:American companies established in 1986]]\n[[Category:Retail companies established in 1986]]\n[[Category:Online retailers of the United States]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Oakland, California]]\n[[Category:Pet stores]]\n[[Category:1986 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Retail companies based in California]]\n[[Category:Pets in the United States]]\n[[Category:Food and drink companies based in California]]\n\n{{US-retail-company-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Sabakhami786", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pet_Food_Express"}
{"title_page": "National day of mourning", "text_new": "{{short description|A day marked by mourning and memorial activities}}\n{{About|the general concept|the equivalent at the European Union level|European Day of Mourning|annual observances|Day of mourning (disambiguation)}}{{Short description|Type of public holiday}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2012}}\n{{more citations needed|date=December 2010}}\n[[File:Half raised flag.jpg|thumb|200px|right|[[Flag of Finland|Finnish flag]] at [[half-staff]] due to the [[2011 Norway attacks]] on 22 July 2011.]]\n\nA '''national day of mourning''' is a day or days marked by [[mourning]] and memorial activities observed among the majority of a country's populace. They are designated by the national government. Such days include those marking the death or funeral of a renowned individual or individuals from that country or elsewhere or the anniversary of such a death or deaths, the anniversaries of a significant natural or man-made disaster occurring either in the country or another country, wartime commemorations, or in memory of the victims of a terrorist attack. Flying a national or military flag of that country at [[half-staff]] is a common symbol.\n{{TOC right}}\n==Selected list of figures recognized==\n\n===State officials===\n\n*[[Mohamed Brahmi]], Tunisian opposition figure and member of the [[Constituent Assembly of Tunisia|Tunisian Constituent Assembly]] was assassinated in front of his house.\n*The Father of the State of Bangladesh, [[Sheikh Mujibur Rahman]] was killed by a group of Bangladesh Army personnel. The officers killed his whole family except his daughters [[Sheikh Hasina]] and [[Sheikh Rehana]].\n*Victims of the 2005 assassination of Former Prime Minister [[Rafik Hariri]] ([[Lebanon]])\n*A National Day of Mourning is typically declared for [[Presidents of the United States]], usually on the day of their funerals. Beginning with [[John F. Kennedy]], these days are also considered federal holidays. There was no official day of mourning for [[Herbert Hoover]].<ref name=\"USStateFunerals\">{{cite web|title=Past State Funerals|url=https://www.usstatefuneral.mdw.army.mil/past-state-funerals|website=usstatefuneral.mdw.army.mil}}</ref>\n*In the [[Soviet Union]], an official mourning period of several days was declared for the deaths of leaders or former leaders, with [[Alexei Rykov]], [[Nikita Khrushchev]] and [[Georgy Malenkov]] being notable exceptions after Rykov was executed during the [[Great Purge]] and the other two were relegated to obscurity. Khrushchev's death was announced only hours before he was buried without full state honors,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gwertzman |first1=Bernard |title=Soviet Announces Khrushchev Death in Cool Language |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1971/09/13/archives/soviet-announces-khrushchev-death-in-cool-language-moscow-denies.html |website=The New York Times |date=September 13, 1971}}</ref> while Malenkov's death was announced more than 2 weeks after his death.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Pearson |first1=Richard |title=George Malenkov Dies |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/local/1988/02/02/georgi-malenkov-dies/8d8ea079-f433-426e-8569-c74801e1f152/ |website=The Washington Post |date=February 2, 1988}}</ref> This custom changed in 1968 when a national day of mourning was declared for Soviet cosmonaut [[Yuri Gagarin]], the first human to journey into outer space.<ref name=Gagarin/> In the final years of the Soviet Union, official mourning was declared for 2 disasters: the [[1988 Armenian earthquake]] and the [[Ufa train disaster]].<ref name=Russia/><ref>{{cite web |title=\u041a\u043e\u0433\u0434\u0430 \u0438 \u043f\u043e \u043a\u0430\u043a\u043e\u043c\u0443 \u043f\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0434\u0443 \u0432 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438 \u043e\u0431\u044a\u044f\u0432\u043b\u044f\u043b\u0438 \u043e\u0431\u0449\u0435\u043d\u0430\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0442\u0440\u0430\u0443\u0440. \u0418\u043d\u0444\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0444\u0438\u043a\u0430 |url=https://www.bbc.com/russian/features-43572739 |website=BBC News \u0420\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0431\u0430 |language=ru |date=March 28, 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Tom\u00e1\u0161 Garrigue Masaryk]] \u2013 First President of Czechoslovakia. National mourning since his death on 14\u201321 September 1937.\n*[[Mustafa Kemal Atat\u00fcrk]] \u2013 founder of the [[Turkey|Republic of Turkey]]. 10 November is the national mourning day in Turkey, commemorating Atat\u00fcrk's death on 10 November 1938. Every year at 09:05 on November 10, sirens are heard across Turkey followed by a minute of tribute as well as cessation of most all activity for that duration.\n*[[Charles de Gaulle]] \u2013 Former [[President of France]] died on 9 November 1970. Declared national mourning the state funeral on 12 November.\n*After the assassination of the [[Sweden|Swedish]] Social Democratic Prime Minister [[Olof Palme]] in 1986\u2013Sweden, Cuba, [[Nicaragua]], and [[Vietnam]].\n*Iran's [[Iranian Revolution|1979 Revolution]]'s leader Ayatollah [[Ruhollah Khomeini]]. Following his death on 3 June 1989, three days of mourning was declared by President [[Ali Khamenei]].\n*Leaders [[Zhou Enlai]], [[Mao Zedong]] (who was given a ''national mourning period'' lasting a week), and [[Deng Xiaoping]]\u2013[[People's Republic Of China]]\n*[[Yitzhak Rabin]], the Prime Minister of [[Israel]] who was [[Assassination of Yitzhak Rabin|assassinated]] on 4 November 1995; a national day of mourning is commemorated in Israel and in various Jewish communities worldwide.\n*[[Emperor Hirohito]] of Japan, who died in January 1989; national mourning was declared for two days<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/01/10/business/mourning-fails-to-slow-japan-s-economy.html|title=Mourning Fails to Slow Japan's Economy|last=Sanger|first=David E.|date=January 10, 1989|work=The New York Times|accessdate=February 8, 2013}}</ref> and the day of his funeral.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1309&dat=19890223&id=gGMmAAAAIBAJ&sjid=IpADAAAAIBAJ&pg=5858,1614497|title=An Emperor's Farewell|work=[[New Straits Times]]|date=February 23, 1989|accessdate=February 8, 2013}}</ref>\n*Former President of France [[Fran\u00e7ois Mitterrand]] died on 8 January 1996. National mourning declared of state funeral on 11 January.\n*[[Indonesia]]n former President [[Suharto]]. Following his death in January 2008, President [[Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono]] declared seven days of national mourning and instructed all government officials, embassies overseas, and all Indonesian citizens to fly the Indonesia flag at half-staff in Soeharto's honor from 27 January to 2 February 2008.\n*Fascist leader of [[Francoist Spain|Spain]] from 1939 to 1975 [[Francisco Franco]]. Twenty days of national mourning were declared following his demise on 20 November 1975.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Payne |first1=Stanley G. |last2=Palacios |first2=Jes\u00fas |title=Franco: A Personal and Political Biography |date=2014 |publisher=University of Wisconsin Pres |isbn=978-0-299-30210-8 |page=499 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rn6aBAAAQBAJ&q=+national+mourning#v=onepage&q=%20mourning&f=false}}</ref>\n*[[Alexander Dub\u010dek]]'s death in 1992, at the time he was the chairman of the Federal Assembly of [[Czechoslovakia]]\n*Former [[President of the Philippines|Philippine President]] [[Corazon Aquino]]. Following her death on 1 August 2009, then-President [[Gloria Macapagal-Arroyo]] declared ten days of national mourning.\n*[[Nigeria]]n President [[Umaru Yar'Adua]] death (mainly African countries)\n*[[Argentina|Argentinean]] President [[N\u00e9stor Kirchner]] (mainly [[Latin America|Latin American countries]])\n*[[Presidents of Mexico]], usually on the day of their funerals (these days are usually considered municipal and religious holidays in [[Mexico City]] and federal holidays in the rest of [[Mexico|the republic]].) [[Miguel de la Madrid]] in 2012 was the most recent.\n*[[Dom Mintoff]]  \u2013 former prime minister of Republic of [[Malta]] died in his home in [[Tarxien]] on 20 August 2012. Days of Mourning: Friday 24 August 2012 and Saturday 25 August 2012.\n*[[Meles Zenawi]]  \u2013 the Prime Minister of [[Ethiopia]] died in a hospital in [[Brussels]] on 20 August 2012. 13 days of state mourning was declared.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Aregay |first1=Daniel |title=Meles Zenawi's 13-day long state mourning ends today |url=https://ethiopiaobservatory.com/2012/09/02/ethiopia-mourns-its-long-term-prime-minister-at-state-funeral/ |website=Ethiopia Observatory |accessdate=August 14, 2018}}</ref>\n*Philippine [[Department of Interior and Local Government (Philippines)|Interior and Local Government Secretary]] [[Jesse Robredo]] who with 2 others was [[2012 Philippine Piper Seneca crash|killed in a plane crash]] on 18 August 2012. 21 to 26 August were declared days of national mourning in the Philippines.\n*[[V\u00f5 Nguy\u00ean Gi\u00e1p]] \u2013 Vietnamese General. Died in military hospital at age 102 on 4 October 2013. 12 and 13 October were declared national mourning days in Vietnam.\n*Former President of [[South Africa]] and [[Internal resistance to South African apartheid|Anti-Apartheid]] campaigner [[Nelson Mandela]], who died on 5 December 2013. Official days of national mourning in [[South Africa]] from 8 December to 15 December 2013, [[Algeria]] eight-day period of mourning<ref>{{cite web|title=President Bouteflika declares 8 days of mourning, flags to be flown at half-mast |url=http://www.aps.dz/President-Bouteflika-declares-8.html |publisher=Alg\u00e9rie Presse Service |accessdate=December 7, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20131207004420/http://www.aps.dz/President-Bouteflika-declares-8.html |archivedate= December 7, 2013  }}</ref>, [[Kenya]] declared three days of national mourning<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.standardmedia.co.ke/?articleID=2000099535&storytitle=uhuru-declares-3-days-of-mourning-mandela |title=Uhuru declares 3 days of mourning Mandela |publisher=Standard Digital News|author=Sd Reporter|date=December 6, 2013}}</ref>, [[Tanzania]] declared three days of national mourning<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.globaltimes.cn/content/830437.shtml |title=Tanzania condoles over death of Mandela |author=Xinhua |date=December 6, 2013|website=Global Times}}</ref>,\n[[India]] declared five-day State Mourning<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/5-day-state-mourning-in-India-as-a-mark-of-respect-to-Nelson-Mandela/articleshow/26957822.cms |title=India to observe 5 Day State Mourning in respect of Nelson Mandela |publisher=The Timesof India|date=December 6, 2013}}</ref>,[[Venezuela]] declared three days of national mourning<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/chi-nelson-mandela-dead-20131205,0,6266118.story |title=Nelson Mandela dead: World mourns loss of 'Madiba' |date= December 6, 2013|author=Tribune Staff |newspaper=Chicago Tribune |access-date=December 6, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131206104712/http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/chi-nelson-mandela-dead-20131205,0,6266118.story |archive-date=December 6, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>[[Dominican Republic]] declared day of mourning in 10 December 2013.<ref>{{cite web |title=Gov't declares national day of mourning for Nelson Mandela |url=https://dominicanewsonline.com/news/homepage/news/human-interest/govt-declares-national-day-mourning-nelson-mandela/ |website=Dominica News Online |date=December 9, 2013}}</ref>\n*Former Prime Minister [[Lee Kuan Yew]], in Singapore, died on 23 March 2015. Official days of national mourning in Singapore was from 23 to 29 March 2015.\n*[[King Abdullah of Saudi Arabia]] died on 23 January 2015. Three days of mourning were held at [[Riyadh]].\n*Former President [[APJ Abdul Kalam]], in India, died on 27 July 2015. Official days of national mourning in India was from 27 July to 2 August 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/former-president-abdul-kalam-hospitalised-in-shillong-after-collapsing-during-speech/article1-1373696.aspx |title='Missile Man': Ex-president APJ Abdul Kalam passes away |work=Hindustan Times |date=July 25, 2015 |accessdate=July 15, 2016}}</ref>\n*President of Uzbekistan [[Islam Karimov]], died on 2 September 2016. Official days of national mourning in [[Uzbekistan]] from 3 to 6 September 2016.\n*Former President of Italy [[Carlo Azeglio Ciampi]], died on 16 September 2016. Official day of national mourning in Italy on 19 September 2016.\n*Former Israeli President [[Shimon Peres]], died on 27 September 2016. The mourning period was initially 30 days, as per Jewish custom called [[Bereavement in Judaism#Stages of Mourning|shloshim]],<ref name=\"JTA \u2013 17-01-17\">{{cite web|title=Shimon Peres tombstone to be unveiled at service marking 30-day mourning period|url=http://www.jta.org/2016/10/27/news-opinion/israel-middle-east/shimon-peres-tombstone-to-be-unveiled-at-service-marking-30-day-mourning-period|website=Jewish Telegraphic Agency|publisher=Jewish Telegraphic Agency|accessdate=17 January 2017}}</ref> but was extended by Peres' family due to popular demand from mourners.<ref name=\"JTA \u2013 17-01-17\"/>\n*Thai King [[Bhumibol Adulyadej]] died on 13 October 2016. His funeral took place within a one-year period of mourning.\n*Former Cuban President [[Fidel Castro]] died on 25 November 2016. Official days of national mourning in Cuba were from 26 November to 4 December.<ref name=\"The Guardian 17-01-17\">{{cite web|last1=Khomami|first1=Nadia|last2=Johnston|first2=Chris|last3=Phipps|first3=Claire|title=Fidel Castro death: Donald Trump hopes for a free Cuba \u2013 as it happened|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2016/nov/26/fidel-castro-death-cuban-leader-live-updates|website=The Guardian|accessdate=17 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Decreta el Consejo de Estado duelo nacional|url=http://www.granma.cu/cuba/2016-11-26/decreta-el-consejo-de-estado-duelo-nacional-26-11-2016-04-11-03|website=Granma|accessdate=26 November 2016|date=26 November 2016|language=Spanish}}</ref> Algeria declared eight days of mourning;<ref name=\"Algeria\">{{cite web|title=D\u00e9c\u00e8s de Fidel Castro: le pr\u00e9sident Bouteflika d\u00e9cr\u00e8te un deuil national de 8 jours|url=https://www.huffpostmaghreb.com/entry/deces-castro-bouteflika_mg_13250346|website=The Huffington Post|accessdate=26 November 2016|date=26 November 2016|language=French}}</ref> Bolivia decreed seven days of national mourning;<ref>{{cite web|title=Bolivia decreta duelo nacional por la muerte de Fidel Castro|url=https://www.huffpostmaghreb.com/entry/deces-castro-bouteflika_mg_13250346|website=Prensa Latina|accessdate=28 November 2016|date=28 November 2016|language=Spanish}}</ref> Equatorial Guinea decreed three days of national mourning;<ref name=\"eqguinea\">{{cite web|title=Duelo nacional en Guinea Ecuatorial por fallecimiento de Fidel Castro|url=http://prensa-latina.cu/index.php?o=rn&id=46097&SEO=duelo-nacional-en-guinea-ecuatorial-por-fallecimiento-de-fidel-castro|website=Prensa Latina|accessdate=29 November 2016|date=29 November 2016|language=Spanish}}</ref> Nicaragua decreed nine days of national mourning;<ref>{{cite web|title=Nicaragua decreta nueve d\u00edas de duelo nacional por muerte de Fidel Castro|url=http://www.elnuevodiario.com.ni/politica/411369-nicaragua-decreta-nueve-dias-duelo-nacional-muerte/|website=El Nuevo Diario|accessdate=28 November 2016|date=26 November 2016|language=Spanish}}</ref> North Korea declared a period of mourning for three days;<ref>{{cite web|title=North Korea declares 3-day mourning for 'close friend and comrade' Fidel Castro|url=https://www.rt.com/news/368389-north-korea-castro-mourning/|publisher=RT|accessdate=28 November 2016|date=28 November 2016}}</ref> and Venezuela decreed three days of national mourning.,<ref>{{cite web|title=Gobierno de Venezuela declara tres d\u00edas de duelo por fallecimiento de Fidel Castro|url=http://globovision.com/article/venezuela-se-solidariza-con-cuba-por-la-muerte-de-fidel-castro|website=Globovisi\u00f3n|accessdate=28 November 2016|date=26 November 2016|language=Spanish}}</ref> Namibia declared a period of mourning for three days<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newera.com.na/2016/12/01/namibia-declares-three-days-of-mourning-for-castro/|title=Namibia declares three days of mourning for Castro|first=New Era Publication|last=Corporation|date=1 December 2016|publisher=|accessdate=28 December 2016}}</ref> Uruguay,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elnuevoherald.com/noticias/mundo/america-latina/article117213703.html|title=Uruguay decreta duelo oficial por la muerte de Fidel Castro|publisher=|accessdate=28 December 2016}}</ref> Vietnam,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://e.vnexpress.net/news/news/vietnam-announces-a-day-of-mourning-for-fidel-castro-3505676.html|title=Vietnam announces a day of mourning for Fidel Castro \u2013 VnExpress International|first=|last=VnExpress|publisher=|accessdate=28 December 2016}}</ref> Angola decreed one day of national mourning;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.angop.ao/angola/en_us/noticias/politica/2016/11/48/Angolan-President-declares-one-day-national-mourning-Fidel-Castro-memory,099475d9-d025-4d03-87e1-0d8a6676ef13.html|title=Angolan President declares one-day national mourning in Fidel Castro's memory|publisher=|accessdate=28 December 2016}}</ref> Trinidad and Tobago decreed that the [[Flag of Trinidad and Tobago|national flag be flown at half-mast]] for one day;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnc3.co.tt/press-release/tt-flags-be-flown-half-mast-today-mourn-fidel-castros-passing|title=T&T flags to be flown at half-mast today to mourn Fidel Castro's passing|publisher=|accessdate=28 December 2016}}</ref> while Haiti decreed three days of mourning;<ref name=\"granma\">{{cite web|title=Mensajes de condolencia de l\u00edderes mundiales|url=http://www.granma.cu/hasta-la-victoria-siempre-fidel/2016-12-03/mensajes-de-condolencia-de-lideres-mundiales-03-12-2016-00-12-06|website=Granma|accessdate=4 December 2016|date=3 December 2014|language=Spanish}}</ref> and Dominica declared national mourning for Castro.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dominicavibes.dm/news-217908/|title=Dominica declares national mourning for Fidel Castro \u2013 Dominica Vibes News|publisher=|accessdate=28 December 2016}}</ref>\n*Former [[Chief Minister of Tamil Nadu]], [[Jayalalithaa]] died on 5 December 2016. National day of mourning on 6 December 2016 by the [[Government of India]]. A seven-day mourning period from 6\u201312 December 2016 was observed by [[Government of Tamil Nadu]],<ref name=\"natmotn\">{{cite news|title=Jayalalithaa death: Centre declares one-day national mourning for Amma, Tricolour to fly at half mast|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/jayalalithaa-dead-centre-declares-one-day-national-mourning-for-amma-4412903/|accessdate=17 December 2016|work=[[Indian Express]]|date=6 December 2016|location=[[New Delhi]]}}</ref> also three day state mourning period from 6\u20138 December 2016 was observed by [[Government of Kerala]],<ref name=\"jker\">{{cite news|title=Three-day official mourning declared in Kerala after Jayalalithaa's demise|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/kerala/2016/dec/06/three-day-official-mourning-declared-in-kerala-after-jayalalithaas-demise-1546234.html|accessdate=17 December 2016|work=[[The New Indian Express]]|date=6 December 2016|location=[[Thiruvananthapuram]]}}</ref> and [[Government of Puducherry]].<ref name=\"jjpy\">{{cite news|title=Jayalalithaa death: Pondicherry announces 3-day state mourning|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/jayalalithaa-death-pondicherry-announces-3-day-state-mourning-4413260/|accessdate=17 December 2016|work=[[Indian Express]]|date=7 December 2016|location=[[Puducherry]]}}</ref>  One day of mourning on 6 December 2016 was observed by [[Government of Karnataka]],<ref name=\"jjka\">{{cite news|title=Jayalalithaa death: Karnataka declares a day of mourning|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/jayalalithaa-death-karnataka-declares-a-day-of-mourning-4413070/|accessdate=17 December 2016|work=[[Indian Express]]|date=6 December 2016|location=[[Bengaluru]]}}</ref> [[Government of Punjab (India)|Government of Punjab]],<ref name=\"jjpunj\">{{cite news|title=One day's state mourning in Punjab on Jayalalithaa's|url=http://www.uniindia.com/one-day-s-state-mourning-in-punjab-on-jayalalithaa-s/states/news/709156.html|accessdate=17 December 2016|work=[[United News of India]]|date=6 December 2016}}</ref> [[Government of Uttarakhand]], and [[Government of Bihar]].<ref name=\"jjuabh\">{{cite news|last1=Ankita|first1=Bhandari|title=Central govt announces one-day mourning after Jayalalithaa's death|url=http://zeenews.india.com/news/tamil-nadu/central-govt-announces-one-day-mourning-after-jayalalithaas-death_1956239.html|accessdate=17 December 2016|work=[[Zee News]]|date=6 December 2016|location=[[New Delhi]]}}</ref>\n\n===Religious figures===\n*[[Iglesia ni Cristo]] Executive Minister [[Era\u00f1o Manalo]], ([[Philippines]]),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/nation/09/04/09/sept-7-21-declared-non-working-holidays |title=Sept 7, 21 declared non-working holidays |publisher=ABS-CBN News |date=2009-09-06 |accessdate=2016-07-15}}</ref>\n*[[Sister L\u00facia]], (Portugal)\n*[[Mother Teresa of Calcutta]], (mainly India, Albania, and some Roman Catholic countries)\n*[[Maxim of Bulgaria|Patriarch Maxim of Bulgaria]] ([[Bulgaria]])\n*[[Serbian Patriarch Pavle]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.b92.net/eng/news/politics-article.php?yyyy=2009&mm=11&dd=16&nav_id=63065 |title=Serbia observes first day of mourning |publisher=B92 |date=2009-11-16 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110608081557/http://www.b92.net/eng/news/politics-article.php?yyyy=2009&mm=11&dd=16&nav_id=63065 |archivedate=2011-06-08}}</ref>\n*[[Pope John Paul II]], (many countries inclu